\begin_layout Abstract
The beta transformation is the iterated map 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta x\,\mod1$
\end_inset

.
 It has interesting number-theoretic properties, in that it generates the
 base-
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 expansion of a real number 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 In the theory of dynamical systems, every iterated piece-wise monotonic
 map is topologically conjugate to the beta transformation.
 For all but a countable subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

, the orbits of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 are ergodic; yet it is the finite and periodic orbits that determine overall
 behavior
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
The beta transform defines a subshift: iterated on the unit interval, it
 singles out a subspace of Cantor space that is invariant under the action
 of the left-shift operator.
 That is, lopping off one bit at a time gives back the same subspace.
 The shift operator can be taken as an infinite-dimensional square matrix
 with positive integer entries; thus the Perron–Frobenius theorem applies.
 The shift operator is a Ruelle–Frobenius–Perron operator.
 The largest eigenvalue corresponds to an invariant measure on the unit
 interval, the Gelfond-Parry measure.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
This text splits into four parts.
 The first part provides a review of general concepts and properties associated
 with the beta transform and the beta shift.
 The second part examines the spectrum of the Ruelle–Frobenius–Perron operator,
 and gives explicit expressions for a set of bounded eigenfunctions.
 These form a discrete spectrum, accumulating on a circle of radius 
\begin_inset Formula $1/\beta$
\end_inset

 in the complex plane.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
The third part of this text examines the finite and the periodic orbits.
 These are in one-to-one correspondence with monic integer polynomials.
 They are 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

quasi-cyclotomic
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and can be counted with Moreau's necklace-counting function; curiously,
 they do not have any obvious relation to other systems countable by the
 necklace function.
 The positive real roots are dense in the reals; they include the Golden
 and silver ratios, the Pisot numbers, the n-bonacci (tribonacci, tetranacci,
 
\emph on
etc.
\emph default
) numbers.
 The beta-polynomials yoke all of these together into a regular structure.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
The fourth part of this text examines small perturbations of the beta transform.
 These introduce Arnold tongues, inflating each periodic orbit into a region
 of finite size.
 The Arnold tongues are in precise (one-to-one) correspondence with the
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

islands of stability
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of the Feigenbaum map.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
This text assumes very little mathematical sophistication on the part of
 the reader, and should be approachable by those with minimal or no prior
 experience in ergodic theory.
 Most of the development is casual.
 As a side effect, the introductory sections are perhaps a fair bit longer
 than strictly needed to present the new results.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Given a real number 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, it can be written down in base-ten, decimal notation, as a string of digits
 0-9.
 Each successive digit is given by an iterated formula.
 Starting with 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{0}=x$
\end_inset

, let
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
y_{n+1}=\left(10y_{n}\right)\mod1
\]

\end_inset

The 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

'th digit in the decimal expansion is 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{n}=\left\lfloor y_{n}\right\rfloor $
\end_inset

.
 Here, mod is the modulo (or remainder) function, so that 
\begin_inset Formula $a\mod b$
\end_inset

 is the remainder of 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 after dividing by 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

.
 The bracket 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\lfloor z\right\rfloor $
\end_inset

 is the floor function, returning the largest integer less than 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

.
 The decimal expansion of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is then 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{0}.d_{1}d_{2}d_{3}\cdots$
\end_inset

 with all digits 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{n}$
\end_inset

 (except for the first) running between 0 and 9.
 The iteration has the form of a shift; it shifts over by one digit, and
 repeats the process.
 The shift is ergodic over the reals: any and every decimal expansion will
 occur.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The same idea can be applied by replacing ten by any number 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

; this gives the base-
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 expansion.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 does not need to be an integer; the rest of this text is focused on exploring
 the expansions coming from 
\begin_inset Formula $1<\beta\le2$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

base two or less
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The beta transformation is the map 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
t_{\beta}\left(x\right)=\beta x\mod1
\]

\end_inset

iterated on the unit interval 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[0,1\right]$
\end_inset

 of the reals, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 taken to be a real positive constant.
 For the special case of 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta=2$
\end_inset

, this is the Bernoulli process, the ergodic process of random coin flips.
 The Bernoulli shift is solvable in more ways than one; it is well-understood,
 and provides a canonical model of ergodic behavior.
 The beta transformation is less well-known and less carefully scrutinized.
 A full review of previous results is presented at the end of this introduction.
 The goal of this text is two-fold: to expand the collection of known properties
, and to present them in the simplest, most accessible fashion possible.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One primary driver of interest in iterated functions is that they generate
 fractals, and that they provide simple models of chaotic dynamics.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

-transform is the simplest possible map that exhibits all of the hallmarks
 of chaotic dynamical systems: a non-trivial, non-uniform invariant measure,
 with both periodic and non-periodic orbits.
 It is also 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

generic
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, in that any other piecewise-monotonic map of the unit interval is topologicall
y conjugate to it.
 If one can understand the 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

-transform, one has gone a long ways towards understanding iterated maps
 in general.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are two broad aproaches for studying iterated functions.
 One is to examine the point dynamics and orbits: 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

where does the point 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 go, when iterated?
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 The other is in terms of distributions: 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

how does a scattered dust of points evolve over time?
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 Within the context of physics, these give two broad views of reality.
 The first is of microscopic, time-reversible systems whose future is determinis
tic and known with infinite precision.
 The second is of macroscopic, time-irreversible thermodynamics, where time
 can only go forward, and the future is unknown and unknowable.
 Of these two approaches, the first is commonplace and inescapable; the
 second remains obscure, poorly-recognized and opaque.
 Thus, a large part of this text is devoted to this second approach.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If iterating a map 
\begin_inset Formula $x\mapsto f\left(x\right)\mapsto f\left(f\left(x\right)\right)\mapsto\cdots$
\end_inset

 pulls a point 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 through 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

, through time, then the action of the map 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 on a distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 is a push-forward: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\rho\left(A\right)\mapsto\rho\left(f^{-1}\left(A\right)\right)\mapsto\rho\left(f^{-1}\left(f^{-1}\left(A\right)\right)\right)\mapsto\cdots
\]

\end_inset

The proper defintion of a pushforward requires a significant development
 of the concepts of measureable spaces and Borel sigma algebras, topics
 that will be gently reviewed a bit further in this introductory section.
 For the present, it is enough to take 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho:\left[0,1\right]\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 to be some fuction defined on the unit interval.
 In the above, 
\begin_inset Formula $A\subset\left[0,1\right]$
\end_inset

 is a subset of the unit interval, so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho\left(A\right)=\int_{A}\rho\left(x\right)dx$
\end_inset

 is an ordinary integral, the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

size
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of the set 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 with respect to the distribution.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The challenge is to find an explicit expression for the pushforward 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho\left(f^{-1}\left(A\right)\right)$
\end_inset

.
 This can be obtained as a change of variable 
\begin_inset Formula $y=f\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 under integration.
 Start with any function 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

; it's integral over the set 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is as above: 
\begin_inset Formula $h\left(A\right)=\int_{A}h\left(y\right)dy$
\end_inset

.
 Under the change of variable, this becomes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
h\left(A\right)=\int_{A}h\left(y\right)dy=\int_{f^{-1}\left(A\right)}h\left(f\left(x\right)\right)\left|f^{\prime}\left(x\right)\right|dx
\]

\end_inset

Writing the integrand as 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho\left(x\right)=h\left(f\left(x\right)\right)\left|f^{\prime}\left(x\right)\right|$
\end_inset

 and working backwards, one recovers
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
h\left(y\right)=\frac{\rho\left(f^{-1}\left(y\right)\right)}{\left|f^{\prime}\left(f^{-1}\left(y\right)\right)\right|}
\]

\end_inset

Plugging this back through gives the identity
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{A}\frac{\rho\left(f^{-1}\left(y\right)\right)}{\left|f^{\prime}\left(f^{-1}\left(y\right)\right)\right|}dy=\int_{f^{-1}\left(A\right)}\rho\left(x\right)dx=\rho\left(f^{-1}\left(A\right)\right)
\]

\end_inset

The right-hand-side is the desired pushforward; the left-hand side is an
 explicit expression for it.
 There was a minor sleight-of-hand in the above derivation: the map 
\begin_inset Formula $y=f\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 may not be one-to-one.
 Thus, there may be several distinct points 
\begin_inset Formula $x=f^{-1}\left(y\right)$
\end_inset

.
 In this case, the above needs to be amended as 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
h\left(y\right)=\sum_{x\in f^{-1}\left(y\right)}\frac{\rho\left(x\right)}{\left|f^{\prime}\left(x\right)\right|}
\]

\end_inset

As 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 depends only on 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

, the sum construction on the right-hand side can be thought of as an operation
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}$
\end_inset

, defined by 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

, acting on 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

; in short-hand, 
\begin_inset Formula $h=\mathcal{L}_{f}\rho$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The symbol 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}$
\end_inset

 is used to remind that this is a linear operator: 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}\left(a\rho+b\sigma\right)=a\mathcal{L}\rho+b\mathcal{L}\sigma$
\end_inset

 for any pair of real numbers 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b$
\end_inset

 and any functions 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho,\sigma$
\end_inset

.
 The pushforward sequence now becomes
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\rho\left(A\right)\mapsto\left[\mathcal{L}_{f}\rho\right]\left(A\right)\mapsto\left[\mathcal{L}_{f}\mathcal{L}_{f}\rho\right]\left(A\right)\mapsto\cdots
\]

\end_inset

Thus, we've defined a linear operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{f}$
\end_inset

 that depends only on the iterated function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

, and has the property of mapping distributions to other distributions as
 it is iterated.
 It is the result of commuting with function composition: 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{f}\circ\rho=\rho\circ f^{-1}$
\end_inset

; it's a kind of a trick with function composition.
 Indeed, one can define an analogoous operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{K}_{f}\circ\rho=\rho\circ f$
\end_inset

, the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

composition operator
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Koopman operator
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, that acts as a kind of (one-sided) inverse to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{f}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Formally, the pushforward 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{f}$
\end_inset

 is called the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

transfer operator
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 or the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Ruelle–\SpecialChar softhyphen
Frobenius–\SpecialChar softhyphen
Perron operator
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 As a linear operator, the full force of operator theory comes into play.
 The primary task is to describe it's spectrum (it's eigenfunctions and
 eigenvalues).
 Two aspects of this spectrum are interesting.
 The first is the so-called 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

invariant measure
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, the distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu:\left[0,1\right]\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 that defines a density on the unit interval that is invariant under the
 application of the pushforward: 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{f}\mu=\mu$
\end_inset

.
 An informal example of such an invariant measure are the rings of Saturn:
 an accumulation of dust and gravel, orbiting Saturn, coupled by gravitation
 to both Saturn and orbiting moons, yet in a stable dynamical distribution.
 This is the physical meaning and importance of the invariant measure; more
 generally, it appears as the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

ground state
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

thermodynamic equilibrium state
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in a vast variety of dyanmicl systems.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Aside from the invariant measure, there is also the question of the rest
 of the spectrum.
 These are described by the eigenfunctions 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 satisfying 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}\rho=\lambda\rho$
\end_inset

.
 By the theorem of Frobenius–Perron, all these other solutions have eigenvalue
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\lambda\right|<1$
\end_inset

.
 In physics, these correspond to the decaying modes, to the distributions
 that disappear over time.
 For the example of Saturn, these are anything not orbiting in the plane
 of the rings: tidal forces and perturbations from the moons will force
 such orbits either into the ring, or crash into the planet, or possibly
 fly away to infinity.
 The other orbits are not stable.
 Thus, a characterization of the decaying spectrum is of general interest.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A much stronger conception is that the decaying spectrum has something to
 do with the irreversibility of time.
 In the macroscopic world, this is plainly obvious.
 In the microscopic world, the laws of physics are manifestly time-reversible.
 Somehow, complex dynamical systems pass through a region of chaotic and
 turbulent motion, culminating in thermodynamic equilibrium.
 The decaying spectrum provides a conceptual framework in which one can
 ponder this transition.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is where the fun begins.
 The spectrum is not a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

fixed thing
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, but depends strongly on the space of fuctions on which 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{f}$
\end_inset

 is allowed to act.
 If one limits oneself to 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 drawn from the space of piece-wise continuous and smooth functions, 
\emph on
i.e.

\emph default
 polynomials, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{f}$
\end_inset

 will in general have a discrete spectrum.
 If instead, 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho\in L^{2}\left[0,1\right]$
\end_inset

 the space of functions that are square-integrable on the unit interval,
 then the spectrum will often be continuous, and perhaps may have a large
 kernel.
 Larger spaces exhibit even wilder behavior: if one asks only that 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 be 
\begin_inset Formula $L^{1}$
\end_inset

-integrable (not square-integrable), then it is possible for continuous-nowhere
 functions to appear as eigenfunctions of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{f}$
\end_inset

.
 An explicit example of the latter is the Minkowski measure for the transfer
 operator of the Minkowski Question Mark function: it vanishes on the rationals,
 but can be integrated just fine; it's integral is the Question Mark function.
 In short, a rich variety can often be found.
 In the present case, it seems, nothing quite this rich, but getting there.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Summary
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This text is quite long and large, as it is a summary of the results from
 a multi-year investigation into the 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

-transform.
 It ranges over a variety of disparate topics.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
\shape italic
Part one
\series default
\shape default
 continues with a general overview of basic concepts, including the Bernoulli
 shift, the defintion of shift spaces in a relatively abstract fashion,
 some basics about the 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

-shift, and a collection of pretty visualizations to anchor and motivate.
 Part one concludes with a short review of prior research into the 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

-shift.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
\shape italic
Part two
\series default
\shape default
 defines and works with the transfer operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{\beta}$
\end_inset

 for the 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

-shift.
 The concept of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

analytic algorithmics
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is introduced, by analogy to the idea of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

analytic combinatorics
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 The Heaviside theta function 
\begin_inset Formula $\Theta\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 can be viewed as the algorithmic snippet 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

if 
\begin_inset Formula $x>0$
\end_inset

 then 1 else 0
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

; eigenfunctions of the transfer operator are series summations over 
\begin_inset Formula $\Theta\left(\beta t_{n}-1\right)$
\end_inset

 for a sequence of iterates 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{n}$
\end_inset

.
 A countable number of eigenvalues 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{\beta}$
\end_inset

 are shown to accumulate on the circle 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\lambda\right|=1/\beta$
\end_inset

 in the complex plane.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
\shape italic
Part three
\series default
\shape default
 takes a close look at those 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 values which are characterized by finite orbits.
 These 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 values have the curious property of being 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

self-describing
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

: they occur as roots of a polynomial generated by the orbit of 
\begin_inset Formula $x=1$
\end_inset

 under the iteration of 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{\beta}\left(x\right)=\beta x\mod1$
\end_inset

.
 The orbit produces a bit-string 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{0}b_{1}\cdots b_{k-1}$
\end_inset

 of binary bits.
 When these are arranged into a polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{n}\left(z\right)=z^{k+1}-b_{0}z^{k}-b_{1}z^{k-1}-\cdots-b_{k-1}z-1$
\end_inset

, the unique real positive root of 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{n}\left(z\right)$
\end_inset

 is then the 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 that generated the orbit: thus, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

self-describing
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{n}\left(z\right)$
\end_inset

 is an odd beast.
 It is 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

quasi-cyclotomic
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, in that the (complex) roots are approximately evenly distributed in an
 approximately circular fashion on the complex plane.
 It is a generator of number sequences that generalize the Fibonacci numbers;
 indeed, the first polynomial in the series, 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{1}\left(z\right)=z^{2}-z-1$
\end_inset

 has the Golden mean 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi=\left(1+\sqrt{5}\right)/2$
\end_inset

 as the (real, positive) root.
 The assortment of popular 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

generalized Fibonacci numbers
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 are all special cases of this class.
 There seems to be a rich associated number theory to go with this, but
 it does not seem to align with any known 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

conventional
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 combinatorics.
 For example, the 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{n}\left(z\right)$
\end_inset

 vaguely resemble polynomials over the field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{2}$
\end_inset

, but that is as far as things seem to go: a vague resemblance.
 It is tempting to guess that ideas, concepts and theorems from Galois theory
 might go through, but they don't: the polynomials don't fit that mold in
 any obvious way.
 It seems to be a large class, but there is no existing theory that it maps
 to.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Such self-describing 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 values are dense in the reals, and can be placed in one-to-one correspondence
 with the dyadic rationals.
 This is not as easy as it sounds: not all possible bit-sequences occur,
 and thus much of the work is to describe the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

valid
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 bit-sequences.
 None-the-less, these can be described, and explicit formulas are given.
 This provides a bijection between the set of valid bit-sequences and the
 set of all bit-sequences; again, an explict expression is provided.
 This bijection allows for a large variety of games to be played.
 The mapping to the dyadic rationals is continuous but not differentiable.
 It can be extended to all reals.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The non-terminating orbits fall into two classes: the ultimately-periodic
 orbits, and the ergodic orbits.
 The ultimately-periodic orbits correspond to rationals, but again, not
 all rationals are 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

valid
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

; they don't form self-describing orbits.
 The above-mentioned bijection saves the day: it maps all rationals to valid
 rationals.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
\shape italic
Part four
\series default
\shape default
 explores perturbations of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

-map.
 The exploration is driven by the idea that the periodic orbits rematerialize
 as the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

islands of stability
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in other iterated systems.
 In the 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

-map, the periodic orbits are dense in 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

, but they form a set of measure zero: they are countable.
 Small perturbations of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

-map give rise to Arnold tongues.
 These are now finite-sized regions occupied by the periodic orbits: these
 are the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

mode-locked
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 regions.
 As noted earlier, the 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

-map is topologically conjugate to 
\emph on
all
\emph default
 piece-wise continuous maps of the unit interval; but this is a very abstract
 statement.
 Explicit examples of mode-locking and Arnold tongues illustrates exactly
 what this conjugacy actually looks like.
 Literally; this section is filled with pretty pictures.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Bernoulli shift
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Bernoulli shift, also known as the bit-shift map, the dyadic transform
 and the full shift, is an iterated map on the unit interval, given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
b(x)=\begin{cases}
2x & \mbox{ for }0\le x<\frac{1}{2}\\
2x-1 & \mbox{ for }\frac{1}{2}\le x\le1
\end{cases}\label{eq:Bernoulli shift}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

It can be written much more compactly as 
\begin_inset Formula $b(x)=2x\mod1$
\end_inset

.
 The symbolic dynamics of this map gives the binary digit expansion of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 That is, write 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
b^{n}(x)=(b\circ b\circ\cdots\circ b)(x)=b(b(\cdots b(x)\cdots))
\]

\end_inset

to denote the 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-fold iteration of 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $b^{0}(x)=x$
\end_inset

.
 The symbolic dynamics is given by the bit-sequence
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
b_{n}\left(x\right)=\begin{cases}
0 & \mbox{ if }0\le b^{n}(x)<\frac{1}{2}\\
1 & \mbox{ if }\frac{1}{2}\le b^{n}(x)\le1
\end{cases}\label{eq:bernoulli-bits}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Attention: 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is a subscript on the left, and a superscript on the right! The left is
 a sequence, the right is an iteration.
 Using the letter 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 one both sides is a convenient abuse of notation.
 Notation will be abused a lot in this text, except when it isn't.
 The symbolic dynamics recreates the initial real number:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
x=\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}b_{n}\left(x\right)2^{-n-1}\label{eq:homomorphism}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

All of this is just a fancy way of saying that a real number can be written
 in terms of it's base-2 binary expansion.
 That is, the binary digits for 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 are the 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{n}=b_{n}\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

, so that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x=0.b_{0}b_{1}b_{2}\cdots
\]

\end_inset

is a representation of a real number with a bit-string.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Bijections
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A variety of mathematical objects that can be placed into a bijection with
 collections of bit-strings, and much of this text is an exploration of
 what happens when this is done.
 There will be several recurring themes; these are reviewed here.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The collection of all infinitely-long bit-strings 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ 0,1\right\} ^{\omega}=\left\{ 0,1\right\} \times\left\{ 0,1\right\} \times\cdots$
\end_inset

 is known as the Cantor space; 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 denotes countable infinity, so this is a countable product of repeated
 copies of two things.
 Closely related is the Cantor set, which is famously the collection of
 points 
\begin_inset Formula $y=\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}b_{n}\left(x\right)3^{-n-1}$
\end_inset

 that results from taking the binary expansion of a real number, and re-expressi
ng it as a base-three expansion.
 The Cantor set can also be constructed by repeatedly removing the middle-third.
 If one is careful that the middle-third is always an open set, what remains
 after a single subtraction is a closed set.
 What remains after infinite repetition is a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

perfect set
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, and a key theorem is that this perfect set is identical to the collection
 of points obtained with the sum above.
 Bouncing between these two distinct constructions requires the definition
 of the product topology on Cantor space, and thence the Borel sigma algebra,
 so that one can work in a consistent way with set complements.
 These ideas will be reviewed as the need arises.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Associated with Cantor space is the infinite binary tree.
 Any given location in the tree can be specified by giving a sequence of
 left-right moves, down the tree, starting at the root.
 Such left-right moves can (of course) be interpreted as bit-strings.
 After a finite number of moves, one arrives at a node, and under that node
 extends another infinite binary tree, just like the original.
 If one has a function 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(b\right)$
\end_inset

 that is defined on every node 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 of the binary tree, then one can compare this function to 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(Lb\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(Rb\right)$
\end_inset

 that result from a left move and a right move.
 If these are equal to each other, or scale in some way when compared to
 the original, or if there exist two other functions 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{L}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{R}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(Lb\right)=g_{L}\left(f\left(b\right)\right)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

, and likewise, that 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(Rb\right)=g_{R}\left(f\left(b\right)\right)$
\end_inset

, then one has fractal self-similarity.
 More explicitly, whenever one has a pair of commuting diagrams, 
\begin_inset Formula $f\circ L=g_{L}\circ f$
\end_inset

 and , 
\begin_inset Formula $f\circ R=g_{R}\circ f$
\end_inset

, then one has a dyadic monoid self-symmetry.
 This is the symmetry of a large class of fractals.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Formalities
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The last paragraph is a bit glib, and so some formalities and examples are
 in order.
 These are all very straightforward and conventional, almost trivial, belaboring
 the obvious.
 Despite the seeming triteness of the next handful of paragraphs, these
 formal definitions will be needed, so as to avoid future ambiguities and
 confusions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{M}=\left\{ L,R\right\} ^{<\omega}$
\end_inset

 denote the collection of finite-length binary strings.
 These can be graded by the length 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

 of the string, so that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbb{M}=\left\{ L,R\right\} ^{<\omega}=\bigcup_{\nu=0}^{\infty}\left\{ L,R\right\} ^{\nu}=\epsilon\cup\left\{ L,R\right\} \cup\left(\left\{ L,R\right\} \times\left\{ L,R\right\} \right)\cup\cdots
\]

\end_inset

with 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon$
\end_inset

 denoting the empty (zero-length) string.
 This can be turned into a monoid by defining multiplication as string concatena
tion: given 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma\in\left\{ L,R\right\} ^{n}$
\end_inset

 some sequence of 
\begin_inset Formula $L,R$
\end_inset

 moves of length 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma^{\prime}\in\left\{ L,R\right\} ^{m}$
\end_inset

 some other sequence of length 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma\gamma^{\prime}\in\left\{ L,R\right\} ^{n+m}$
\end_inset

 is some other string of length 
\begin_inset Formula $m+n$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This set is in bijection to the integers in a straight-forward way.
 This bijection, written as 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa:\left\{ L,R\right\} ^{<\omega}\to\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

, can be defined recursively, by a simple commuting diagram.
 Define 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa\left(\epsilon\right)=1$
\end_inset

 and ask that 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa\left(L\gamma\right)=2\kappa\left(\gamma\right)$
\end_inset

 and that 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa\left(R\gamma\right)=2\kappa\left(\gamma\right)+1$
\end_inset

 for every 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma\in\left\{ L,R\right\} ^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa\left(L\right)=2$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa\left(R\right)=3$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $LL,LR,RL,RR$
\end_inset

 map to 
\begin_inset Formula $4,5,6,7$
\end_inset

 respectively.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This bijection commutes with the canonical 
\begin_inset Formula $L,R$
\end_inset

 moves on the natural numbers.
 Write these as a pair of functions 
\begin_inset Formula $L:\mathbb{N}\to\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $R:\mathbb{N}\to\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

, defined as 
\begin_inset Formula $L:m\mapsto2m$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $R:m\mapsto2m+1$
\end_inset

.
 Interpreting these as strings, one promptly has a pair of commuting diagrams
 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa\circ L=L\circ\kappa$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa\circ R=R\circ\kappa$
\end_inset

.
 True formality would have required writing 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa\circ L_{s}=L_{\mathbb{N}}\circ\kappa$
\end_inset

 or even that 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa\left(L_{s}\gamma\right)=L_{\mathbb{N}}\left(\kappa\left(\gamma\right)\right)$
\end_inset

 in order to remind us that 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{s}$
\end_inset

 is a string (of length one) concatenated onto some other string 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

, while 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{\mathbb{N}}$
\end_inset

 is a map of the natural numbers.
 It is convenient to drop these labels, as they mostly serve to clutter
 the text.
 The intended meaning is always clear from context.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Associated with the set 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ L,R\right\} ^{<\omega}$
\end_inset

 is a binary tree 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{B}$
\end_inset

.
 It can be defined as a graph of vertexes 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{j}$
\end_inset

 and edges 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{ij}$
\end_inset

 connecting vertex 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{i}$
\end_inset

 to vertex 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{j}$
\end_inset

.
 Formally, it is the graph 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{B}=\left\{ v_{i},e_{ij}:i\in\mathbb{N},j\in\left\{ 2i,2i+1\right\} \right\} $
\end_inset

.
 Every vertex 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{i}\in\mathbb{B}$
\end_inset

 can be given an integer label: it is just the integer 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 itself.
 To formalize this, there is a map 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta:\mathbb{N}\to\mathbb{B}$
\end_inset

 that provides this labelling.
 The canonical labelling gives the root node a label of 1, the left and
 right sub-nodes 2,3, and so on.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The canonical moves on this binary tree are 
\begin_inset Formula $L:\mathbb{B}\to\mathbb{B}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $R:\mathbb{B}\to\mathbb{B}$
\end_inset

 defined by 
\begin_inset Formula $L:v_{i}\mapsto v_{2i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $L:v_{i}\mapsto v_{2i+1}$
\end_inset

.
 Just as above, these commute with the left and right moves on the integers.
 So, 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta\circ L=L\circ\eta$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta\circ R=R\circ\eta$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The pattern repeats.
 Consider the set 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{D}$
\end_inset

 of dyadic rationals between zero and one.
 These are fractions that can be written as 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(2n+1\right)/2^{m}$
\end_inset

 for some non-negative integers 
\begin_inset Formula $m,n$
\end_inset

.
 These are in one-to-one correspondence with the integers: there is a canonical
 bijection is 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta:\mathbb{D}\to\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

 given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta:\left(2n+1\right)/2^{m}\mapsto2^{m-1}+n$
\end_inset

.
 There are obvious left and right moves, given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta\circ L=L\circ\delta$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta\circ R=R\circ\delta$
\end_inset

.
 So, for example, 
\begin_inset Formula $L\left(1/2\right)=1/4$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $R\left(1/2\right)=3/4$
\end_inset

.
 Viewed as a tree, this places 1/2 at the root of the tree, and 1/4 and
 3/4 as the nodes to the left and right.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
All of these maps were bijections: they are all invertable.
 They place elements of all four objects 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{M},\mathbb{N},\mathbb{B},\mathbb{D}$
\end_inset

 in one-to-one correspondence with each other.
 The commutation of the 
\begin_inset Formula $L,R$
\end_inset

 moves guarantees that the multiplication on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{M}$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 string concatenation, allows elements 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma\in\mathbb{M}$
\end_inset

 to act on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{N},\mathbb{B},\mathbb{D}$
\end_inset

 in the obvious, intended way.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Example: Julia Sets
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As a practical example of the above machinery, consider the Julia set of
 the Mandelbrot map.
 Recall the Mandelbrot map is an iterated map on the complex plane, given
 by 
\begin_inset Formula $z\mapsto z^{2}+c$
\end_inset

.
 The Julia set is the set of points of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

where things came from
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in the Mandelbrot map; it is the inverse 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

map
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $z\mapsto\pm\sqrt{z-c}$
\end_inset

.
 The word 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

map
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is in scare quotes, as the plus-minus in front of the square root indicate
 that each 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 maps to either one of two distinct predecessors.
 The choice of the plus-minus signs can be interpreted as left-right moves,
 and so the Julia set can be interpreted as a representation of the binary
 tree, with it's elements labelled by integers, or dyadic fractions, or
 nodes in the binary tree, or strings of ones and zeros.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We take a moment to make this explicit.
 Fix a point 
\begin_inset Formula $c\in\mathbb{C}$
\end_inset

 in the complex plane.
 Define a function 
\begin_inset Formula $j_{c}:\mathbb{N}\to\mathbb{C}$
\end_inset

 recursively, by writing 
\begin_inset Formula $j_{c}\left(1\right)=0$
\end_inset

 and then 
\begin_inset Formula $j_{c}\left(2m\right)=-\sqrt{j_{c}\left(m\right)-c}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $j_{c}\left(2m+1\right)=+\sqrt{j_{c}\left(m\right)-c}$
\end_inset

.
 Equivalently, there are a pair of moves on the complex plane, 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{c}:\mathbb{C}\to\mathbb{C}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{c}:\mathbb{C}\to\mathbb{C}$
\end_inset

 given by 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{c}:z\to-\sqrt{z-c}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{c}:z\to+\sqrt{z-c}$
\end_inset

 which commute with the Julia map: 
\begin_inset Formula $j_{c}\circ L=L_{c}\circ j_{c}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $j_{c}\circ R=R_{c}\circ j_{c}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The skeleton of the Julia set is a set of points in the complex plane:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbb{J}_{c}=\left\{ z\in\mathbb{C}:z=j_{c}\left(n\right),n\in\mathbb{N}\right\} 
\]

\end_inset

The full Julia set is the closure 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\mathbb{J}}_{c}$
\end_inset

 which includes all of the limit points of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{J}_{c}$
\end_inset

.
 The set 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{J}_{c}$
\end_inset

 is countable; the closure 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\mathbb{J}}_{c}$
\end_inset

 is uncountable.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Example: de Rham Curves
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The above construction generalizes.
 Given any pair of functions 
\begin_inset Formula $f:X\to X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g:X\to X$
\end_inset

 and a point 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}\in X$
\end_inset

 for any space 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, the dyadic monoid induces a map 
\begin_inset Formula $j:\mathbb{N}\to X$
\end_inset

 given recursively as 
\begin_inset Formula $j\left(1\right)=x_{0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $j\left(2m\right)=f\left(j\left(m\right)\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $j\left(2m+1\right)=g\left(j\left(m\right)\right)$
\end_inset

.
 As a commuting diagram, one has that 
\begin_inset Formula $j\circ L=f\circ j$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $j\circ R=g\circ j$
\end_inset

.
 This in turn induces a set 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{J}=\left\{ x\in X:x=j\left(n\right),n\in\mathbb{N}\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 If the space 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is a topological space, so that limits can be meaningfully taken, then
 one also has the closure 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\mathbb{J}}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In 1957, Georges de Rham notes that if 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is a topological space, so that continuity can be defined, and if there
 exist two points 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{a},x_{b}\in X$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $g\left(x_{a}\right)=f\left(x_{b}\right)$
\end_inset

, then the set 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\mathbb{J}}$
\end_inset

 is a continuous curve.
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "DeRham57"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 The original proof also requires that 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be a metric space, and that the two functions 
\begin_inset Formula $f,g$
\end_inset

 be suitably contracting, so that the set 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{J}$
\end_inset

 remains compact.
 More precisely, so that the Banach fixed-point theorem can be applied,
 giving two fixed points 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{a}=f\left(x_{a}\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{b}=g\left(x_{b}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Without compactness, the curve wanders off to infinity, where conceptions
 of continuity break down.
 It is no longer a curve, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

out there
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The continuity condition 
\begin_inset Formula $g\left(x_{a}\right)=f\left(x_{b}\right)$
\end_inset

 and the fixed points have a direct interpretation from the viewpoint of
 the binary tree 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{B}$
\end_inset

.
 Pick a point 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

, any point at all, and make nothing but left moves: the infinite string
 
\begin_inset Formula $LLL\cdots$
\end_inset

.
 The map converts this to the iteration 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(f\left(\cdots\left(x\right)\right)\right)$
\end_inset

 which converges onto the fixed point 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{a}=f\left(x_{a}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Likewise, all right-moves converge onto 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{b}=g\left(x_{b}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 In between, there all other branches in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{B}$
\end_inset

; but there are also the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

gaps
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in between the branches.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider the two paths 
\begin_inset Formula $RLLL\cdots$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $LRRR\cdots$
\end_inset

 down the tree.
 Both start at the root, but end up at different places.
 Yet, they are immediate neighbors: there are no other branches 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

in between
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 these two.
 Such immediate neighbors always lie at either end of a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

gap
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 Each gap is headed up by the root that sits immediately above them, so
 that each gap can be labelled by the node from which these two distinct
 branches diverged.
 The continuity condition asks that these gaps be closed up: the requirement
 that 
\begin_inset Formula $g\left(x_{a}\right)=f\left(x_{b}\right)$
\end_inset

 is the requirement that the two sides of the central gap converge to the
 same point.
 The curve becomes continuous at this point.
 By self-similarity, each gap in the tree closes up; the curve is continuous
 at all such gaps.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As a specific example, consider 
\begin_inset Formula $X=\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x\right)=x/2$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g\left(x\right)=\left(x+1\right)/2$
\end_inset

.
 The fixed points are 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(0\right)=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g\left(1\right)=1$
\end_inset

 and the continuity condition is satsified: 
\begin_inset Formula $g\left(0\right)=f\left(1\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Iteration produces a curve that is just all of the real numbers of the
 unit interval.
 This curve is just the standard mapping of the Cantor space to the unit
 interval: it is one-to-one for all points that are not dyadic rationals,
 and it is two-to-one at the dyadic rationals, as the continuity condition
 explicitly forces the two-to-one mapping.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that Julia sets are not de Rham curves: they don't satisfy the continuity
 criterion.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Shifts
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Adjoint to the left and right moves is a shift 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 that undoes what the L and R moves do.
 It cancels them out, so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau\circ L=\tau\circ R=e$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

 the identity function.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Given a string 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma\in\mathbb{M}$
\end_inset

 of length 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

, consisting of letters 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{0}a_{1}\cdots a_{\nu-1}$
\end_inset

 so that each 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{k}\in\left\{ L,R\right\} $
\end_inset

 is a single letter, define the shift 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau:\mathbb{M}\to\mathbb{M}$
\end_inset

 as the function that lops off a single letter from the front, so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau:a_{0}a_{1}\cdots a_{\nu-1}\mapsto a_{1}a_{2}\cdots a_{\nu-1}$
\end_inset

 is a string that is one letter shorter.
 This shift is adjoint to the moves 
\begin_inset Formula $L,R$
\end_inset

, which prepend either L or R to the string.
 That is, 
\begin_inset Formula $L:\mathbb{M}\to\mathbb{M}$
\end_inset

 which acts on strings as 
\begin_inset Formula $L:\gamma\mapsto L\gamma$
\end_inset

, and likewise, 
\begin_inset Formula $R:\gamma\mapsto R\gamma$
\end_inset

.
 Then, taken as functions, 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau\circ L=\tau\circ R=e$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

 being the identity function on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{M}$
\end_inset

, the function that does nothing.
 The shift 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 is only an adjoint, not an inverse, since there is no way to reattach what
 was lopped off, at least, not without knowing what it was in the first
 place.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $L\circ\tau\ne e\ne R\circ\tau$
\end_inset

.
 The maps 
\begin_inset Formula $L,R$
\end_inset

 were one-to-one but not onto; the map 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 is onto but not one-to-one.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The shift can be composed with either 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa$
\end_inset

 or with 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

, to have the obvious effect.
 It's handy to introduce a new letter and a new function 
\begin_inset Formula $T:\mathbb{N}\to\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

 so that one has 
\begin_inset Formula $T\circ\kappa=\kappa\circ\tau$
\end_inset

 acting as 
\begin_inset Formula $T\left(2m\right)=T\left(2m+1\right)=m$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 applied to the empty string returns the empty string, so also 
\begin_inset Formula $T\left(1\right)=1$
\end_inset

.
 Recycling the same letter 
\begin_inset Formula $T:\mathbb{D}\to\mathbb{D}$
\end_inset

 and defining it so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta\circ T=T\circ\delta$
\end_inset

 one can infer that 
\begin_inset Formula $Tx=2x\mod1$
\end_inset

 for any 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathbb{D}$
\end_inset

.
 So, for example, 
\begin_inset Formula $T\left(1/4\right)=T\left(3/4\right)=1/2$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
On the binary tree 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{B}$
\end_inset

, the shift moves back up the tree, from either the left or the right side.
 That is, given a vertex 
\begin_inset Formula $v\in\mathbb{B}$
\end_inset

, it is the map 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau:v_{2m}\mapsto v_{m}$
\end_inset

 and likewise 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau:v_{2m+1}\mapsto v_{m}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For the Julia set example, it has a meaningful form: 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau:z=j_{c}\left(n\right)\mapsto z^{2}+c$
\end_inset

.
 It re-does what the two Julia set maps undid.
 It is onto: it maps 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{J}_{c}$
\end_inset

 into all of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{J}_{c}$
\end_inset

, and likewise 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\mathbb{J}}_{c}$
\end_inset

 onto 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\mathbb{J}}_{c}$
\end_inset

.
 For the de Rham curve example, it maps thecurve back onto itself.
 In all three examples, these sets are fixed points of 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

.
 Taking 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{J}_{c}\subset\mathbb{C}$
\end_inset

 as a subset of the complex plane, it is invariant under the action of 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

, so that one has 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau\left(\mathbb{J}_{c}\right)=\mathbb{J}_{c}$
\end_inset

 and likewise 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau\left(\mathbb{\overline{\mathbb{J}}}_{c}\right)=\mathbb{\overline{\mathbb{J}}}_{c}$
\end_inset

.
 Likewise, the de Rham curve stays fixed in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 These are all examples of invariant subspaces.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Completions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The previous section defined a binary tree 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{B}$
\end_inset

, but this tree is not the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

infinite binary tree
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 alluded to in the opening paragraphs.
 It is incomplete, in that it does not go 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

all the way down
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 to it's leaves.
 It is not compact, in the same sense that the dyadic fractions 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{D}$
\end_inset

 are not compact: the limit points are absent.
 The Cantor tree 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\mathbb{B}}$
\end_inset

 is the closure or completion ore compactification of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{B}$
\end_inset

; it contains all infinitely-long branches, all the way down to the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

leaves
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of the tree.
 The Cantor tree 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\mathbb{B}}$
\end_inset

 is in one-to-one correspondence with the Cantor space 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ 0,1\right\} ^{\omega}$
\end_inset

, and both can be mapped down to the reals on the unit interval, using eqn
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:homomorphism"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 None of this is particularly deep, but a few paragraphs to articulate these
 ideas will help avoid later confusion and imprecision.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To convert letter strings to binary strings, define a function 
\begin_inset Formula $b:\mathbb{M}\to\left\{ 0,1\right\} $
\end_inset

 such that it returns 0 if the first letter of a string is L, and otherwise
 it returns 1.
 If the string is of zero length, then one has a choice: one can take 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 to be undefined, or let it be 0, or 1, or introduce a wild-card character
 
\begin_inset Formula $*=0\vee1$
\end_inset

 denoting 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

either zero or one
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 For the present, any of these choices is satisfactory.
 The wildcard is appealing when working with the product topology; but,
 at the moment, we have no topologies at play.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To extract the 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

'th letter from a string, define 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{n}:\mathbb{M}\to\left\{ 0,1\right\} $
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{n}=b\circ\tau^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, given 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma\in\mathbb{M}$
\end_inset

 of length 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

, one can create a bitstring 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{0}b_{1}\cdots b_{\nu-1}$
\end_inset

.
 It can be assigned the obvious numerical value:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left[\delta^{-1}\circ\kappa\right]\left(\gamma\right)=\sum_{n=0}^{\nu-1}b_{n}\left(\gamma\right)2^{-n-1}
\]

\end_inset

Comparing this to eqn 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:homomorphism"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, the completion is obvious: 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{M}=\left\{ L,R\right\} ^{<\omega}$
\end_inset

 is completed as 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\mathbb{M}}=\left\{ L,R\right\} ^{\omega}$
\end_inset

 so that it contains all strings of infinite length.
 This is consistent with the completion of the dyadic rationals 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{D}$
\end_inset

 being the entire real unit interval: 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\mathbb{D}}=\left[0,1\right]$
\end_inset

.
 There is no completion 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\mathbb{N}}$
\end_inset

 of the countable numbers, at least, not unless one wishes to say that it
 is the uncountable infinity.
 This could be done, but then the games gets even more circular, as this
 completion is just the Cantor set, and we already have that.
 It seems best to leave 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\mathbb{N}}$
\end_inset

 undefined, to avoid circular confusions.
 The completion 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\mathbb{B}}$
\end_inset

 engenders similar confusion.
 In the original definition, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{B}$
\end_inset

 was defined as a graph with a countable number of vertexes, each labelled
 with an integer.
 This labeling must be abandoned: 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\mathbb{B}}$
\end_inset

 is a graph with an uncountable number of vertexes, each labeled by an element
 from 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\mathbb{M}}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The distinction between 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\mathbb{M}}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\mathbb{B}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ 0,1\right\} ^{\omega}$
\end_inset

 becomes hard to maintain at this point: they are all isomrphic.
 The distinction between 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\mathbb{M}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ 0,1\right\} ^{\omega}$
\end_inset

 is particularly strained: they are both collections of strings in two symbols.
 The primary purpose of trying to maintain this distinction is to remind
 that 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\mathbb{M}}$
\end_inset

 should be though of as a collection of actions that can be applied to sets,
 while 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ 0,1\right\} ^{\omega}$
\end_inset

 is a set, a collection of points that sometimes act as labels for things.
 This distinction is useful for avoiding off-by-one mistakes during calculations
; it is a notational convenience.
 This is a variant of common practice in textbooks: after showing that two
 things are isomorphic, only rarely is the notation collapsed into one big
 tangle.
 One maintains a Rosetta Stone of different ways of writing the same thing.
 And so here: a distinction without a difference.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Shift space
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The shift 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 was defined above as an operator that takes a sequence of letters, and
 lops off the left-most symbol, returning a new sequence that is the remainder
 of the string.
 A shift space 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 is any subset of the set of all infinite strings that remains invariant
 under the shift: 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau S=S$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In general settings, one considers a vocabulary of 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 letters, and the set of infinite sequences 
\begin_inset Formula $N^{\omega}$
\end_inset

, so that a shift space 
\begin_inset Formula $S\subseteq N^{\omega}$
\end_inset

 is a subset of the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

full shift
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $N^{\omega}$
\end_inset

 (which is trivially invariant under 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

).
 Shifts that are proper subsets of a full shift will be called subshifts.
 For the Bernoulli shift, there are 
\begin_inset Formula $N=2$
\end_inset

 letters, and the Bernoulli shift is by defintion the full shift 
\begin_inset Formula $2^{\omega}=\left\{ 0,1\right\} ^{\omega}$
\end_inset

.
 A trivial example of a subshift that is not a full shift is the set 
\begin_inset Formula $S=\left\{ 0^{\omega},1^{\omega}\right\} $
\end_inset

; it has two elements, and is obviously invariant; both 
\begin_inset Formula $0^{\omega}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $1^{\omega}$
\end_inset

 are fixed points of 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

.
 Another example is 
\begin_inset Formula $S=\left\{ \left(01\right)^{\omega},\left(10\right)^{\omega}\right\} $
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(01\right)^{\omega}=0101\cdots$
\end_inset

 is a repeating periodic string.
 Any collection of such periodic strings forms a subshift.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Clearly, the union of two subshifts is a subshift, and so, to classify subshifts
, one wants to find all of the indecomposable pieces, and characterize those.
 Factors include periodic strings of fixed period; but not all of these
 are unique: so, the period-4 string 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(0101\right)^{\omega}$
\end_inset

 is really just the period-two string in disguise.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Subshifts consisting entirely of periodic strings can be characterized in
 terms of Lyndon words.
 Lyndon words are fixed length strings that are not decomposable into shorter
 sequences.
 Thus, each one characterizes a periodic subshift.
 Cyclic permutations of a Lyndon word give the same subshift; for example,
 both 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(01\right)^{\omega}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(10\right)^{\omega}$
\end_inset

 belong to the same subshift.
 The number of distinct, unique subshifts of length 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

 is given by Moreau's necklace counting function: it counts the number of
 distinct sequences of a given length, modulo cyclic permutations thereof.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Characterizing the subshifts that do not consist of periodic orbits is considera
bly harder.
 For example, consider the string 
\begin_inset Formula $s=010^{\omega}$
\end_inset

.
 It has an orbit: 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau s=10^{\omega}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau^{2}s=0^{\omega}$
\end_inset

 and so one can write down a set 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle s\right\rangle =\left\{ 010^{\omega},10^{\omega},0^{\omega}\right\} $
\end_inset

 which has the property that 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau\left\langle s\right\rangle \subset\left\langle s\right\rangle $
\end_inset

.
 However, it is not a subshift, because 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau\left\langle s\right\rangle \ne\left\langle s\right\rangle $
\end_inset

.
 The first two points 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

wander away
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 under the application of the shift; they are part of the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

wandering set
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 What remains is the fixed point 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau0^{\omega}=0^{\omega}$
\end_inset

.
 The ergodic decomposition theorem states that all such sets 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 having the property that 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau X\subset X$
\end_inset

 can be decomposed into two pieces: 
\begin_inset Formula $X=S\cup W$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 a subshift, 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau S=S$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

 the wandering set or dissipative set, that eventually dissipates into the
 empty set: 
\begin_inset Formula $\lim_{n\to\infty}\tau^{n}W=\varnothing$
\end_inset

.
 Subshifts are fixed-points; everything else disappears.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Given some real number 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\left[0,1\right]$
\end_inset

, and it's binary expansion 
\begin_inset Formula $x=0.b_{0}b_{1}\cdots$
\end_inset

, defined in eqn 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:bernoulli-bits"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, what is the nature of 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle s\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $s=b_{0}b_{1}\cdots$
\end_inset

 ? That is, defining
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left\langle s\right\rangle =\left\{ \gamma=\tau^{n}s:n\in\mathbb{N}\right\} 
\]

\end_inset

what portion of 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle s\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 is wandering, and which part is a subshift? If 
\begin_inset Formula $x=p/q$
\end_inset

 is a rational number, the answer is easy: rational numbers have binary
 expansions that are eventually periodic.
 They consist of some finite-length prefix of non-repeating digits, folowed
 by an infinite-length cyclic orbit.
 The finite-length prefix is the wandering set; the cyclic part is a subshift.
 If the period of the cyclic part is 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

, then the subshift contains precisely 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

 elements.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For the Bernoulli shift 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau x=2x\mod1$
\end_inset

, for the real numbers, the answer is provided by the ergodic theorem.
 For all real numbers 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\left[0,1\right]\backslash\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

, that is, the unit interval excluding the rationals, the orbit of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is ergodic: given any real number 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon>0$
\end_inset

 and any 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in\left[0,1\right]$
\end_inset

 there exists some 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|y-\tau^{n}x\right|<\varepsilon$
\end_inset

.
 Iteration takes 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 arbitrarily close to any location on the unit interval.
 In terms of symbolic dynamics, the binary expansion of 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 and the binary expansion of 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau^{n}x$
\end_inset

 will have 
\begin_inset Formula $m=\left\lfloor \log_{2}\varepsilon\right\rfloor $
\end_inset

 digits in common.
 The number 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 can be made arbitrarily large; the subsequence will occur somewhere in
 the expansion.
 Put differently, every finite-length string 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma\in\left\{ 0,1\right\} ^{<\omega}$
\end_inset

 occurs as a prefix of (uncountably many) of the strings in 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle x\right\rangle $
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In essence, that takes care of that, for the Bernoulli shift, at least,
 if one is looking at it from the point of view of point dynamics.
 As long as one thinks with the mind-set of points and their orbits, there
 is not much more to be said.
 The above is, in a sense, a complete description of the Bernoulli shift.
 But the introduction to this text gave lie to this claim.
 If one instead looks at the shift in terms of it's transfer operator acting
 on distributions, then much more can be said.
 The spectrum of the transfer operator is non-trivial, and the eigenfunctions
 are fractal, in general.
 This will be examined more carefully, later; but for now, the topic of
 point dynamics in the Bernoulli shift is exhausted.
 This is the end of the line.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Bernoulli shift is not the only shift on Cantor space.
 And so, onward ho.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Beta shift
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The beta shift is similar to the Bernoulli shift, replacing the number 2
 by a constant real-number value 
\begin_inset Formula $1<\beta\le2$
\end_inset

.
 It can be defined as 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
T_{\beta}(x)=\begin{cases}
\beta x & \mbox{ for }0\le x<\frac{1}{2}\\
\beta\left(x-\frac{1}{2}\right) & \mbox{ for }\frac{1}{2}\le x\le1
\end{cases}\label{eq:downshift}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

This map, together with similar maps, is illustrated in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Iterated-piece-wise-linear"

\end_inset

 below.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Just as the Bernoulli shift generates a sequence of digits, so does the
 beta shift: write
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
k_{n}=\begin{cases}
0 & \mbox{ if }0\le T_{\beta}^{n}\left(x\right)<\frac{1}{2}\\
1 & \mbox{ if }\frac{1}{2}\le T_{\beta}^{n}\left(x\right)\le1
\end{cases}\label{eq:down-bits}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Given the symbolic dynamics, one can reconstruct the original value whenever
 
\begin_inset Formula $1<\beta$
\end_inset

 as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x=\frac{k_{0}}{2}+\frac{1}{\beta}\left(\frac{k_{1}}{2}+\frac{1}{\beta}\left(\frac{k_{2}}{2}+\frac{1}{\beta}\left(\frac{k_{3}}{2}+\frac{1}{\beta}\left(\cdots\right)\right)\right)\right)
\]

\end_inset

Written this way, the 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{\beta}(x)$
\end_inset

 clearly acts as a shift on this sequence:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
T_{\beta}\left(x\right)=\frac{k_{1}}{2}+\frac{1}{\beta}\left(\frac{k_{2}}{2}+\frac{1}{\beta}\left(\frac{k_{3}}{2}+\frac{1}{\beta}\left(\frac{k_{4}}{2}+\frac{1}{\beta}\left(\cdots\right)\right)\right)\right)
\]

\end_inset

In this sense, this shift is 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

exactly solvable
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

: the above provides a closed-form solution for iterating and un-iterating
 the sequence.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Multiplying out the above sequence, one obtains the so-called 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

-expansion
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of a real number 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, namely the series
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
x=\frac{1}{2}\,\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}\frac{k_{n}}{\beta^{n}}\label{eq:shift series}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The bit-sequence that was extracted by iteration can be used to reconstruct
 the original real number.
 Setting 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta=2$
\end_inset

 in eqn 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:down-bits"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 gives the Bernoulli shift: 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{2}\left(x\right)=b\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Unlike the Bernoulli shift, not every possible bit-sequence occurs in this
 system.
 It is a subshift of the full shift: it is a subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ 0,1\right\} ^{\omega}$
\end_inset

 that is invariant under the action of 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{\beta}$
\end_inset

.
 The structure of this shift is explored in detail in a later section.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Associated polynomial
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The iterated shift can also be written as a finite sum.
 A later section will be devoted entirely to the properties of this sum.
 Observe that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
T_{\beta}(x)=\beta\left(x-\frac{k_{0}}{2}\right)
\]

\end_inset

and that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
T_{\beta}^{2}(x)=\beta^{2}x-\frac{\beta}{2}\left(\beta k_{0}+k_{1}\right)
\]

\end_inset

and that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
T_{\beta}^{3}(x)=\beta^{3}x-\frac{\beta}{2}\left(\beta^{2}k_{0}+\beta k_{1}+k_{2}\right)
\]

\end_inset

The general form is then:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
T_{\beta}^{p}(x)=\beta^{p}x-\frac{\beta}{2}\sum_{m=0}^{p-1}k_{m}\beta^{p-m-1}\label{eq:iterated shift}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Since the 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{m}$
\end_inset

 depend on both 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 and on 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, and are only piece-wise continuous functions, this is not a true polynomial.
 It does provide a polynomial-like representation with a range of interesting
 properties.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Density Visualizations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The long-term dynamics of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

-shift can be visualized by means of a bifurcation diagram.
 The idea of a bifurcation diagram gained fame with the Feigenbaum map (shown
 in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
