\begin_layout Subsection
Beta Transformation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
After exactly one iteration of the beta shift, all initial points 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta/2\le x\le1$
\end_inset

 are swept up into the domain 
\begin_inset Formula $0\le x<\beta/2$
\end_inset

, and never leave.
 Likewise, the range of the iterated beta-shift is 
\begin_inset Formula $0\le x<\beta/2$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, an alternative representation of the beta shift, filling the entire
 unit square, can be obtained by dividing both the domain and range by 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta/2$
\end_inset

 to obtain the function
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
t_{\beta}(u)=\begin{cases}
\beta u & \mbox{ for }0\le u<\frac{1}{\beta}\\
\beta u-1 & \mbox{ for }\frac{1}{\beta}\le u\le1
\end{cases}\label{eq:beta transform}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

This can be written more compactly as 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{\beta}\left(x\right)=\beta x\mod1$
\end_inset

.
 In this form, the function is named 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

the beta-transform
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, written as the 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

-transformation, presenting a typesetting challenge to search engines when
 used in titles of papers.
 The orbit of a point 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 in the beta-shift is identical to the orbit of a point 
\begin_inset Formula $u=2x/\beta$
\end_inset

 in the beta-transformation.
 Explicitly comparing to the beta-shift of eqn 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:downshift"

\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
T_{\beta}^{n}\left(x\right)=\frac{\beta}{2}t_{\beta}^{n}\left(\frac{2x}{\beta}\right)\label{eq:xform-shift equivalence}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The beta-shift and the 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

-transformation are essentially the same function; this text works almost
 exclusively with the beta-shift, and is thus idiosyncratic, as it flouts
 the more common convention of working with the 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

-transformation.
 The primary reason for this is a historical quirk, as this text was started
 before the author became aware of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

-transformation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
After a single iteration of the tent map, a similar situation applies.
 After one iteration, all initial points 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta/2\le x\le1$
\end_inset

 are swept up into the domain 
\begin_inset Formula $0\le x<\beta/2$
\end_inset

.
 After a finite number of iterations, all points 
\begin_inset Formula $0<x\le\beta\left(1-\beta/2\right)$
\end_inset

 are swept up, so that the remaining iteration takes place on the domain
 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta\left(1-\beta/2\right)<x<\beta/2$
\end_inset

.
 It is worth defining a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

sidetent
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 function, which corresponds to the that part of the tent map in which iteration
 is confined.
 It is nothing more than a rescaling of the tent map, ignoring those parts
 outside of the above domain that wander away.
 The sidetent is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
s_{\beta}(u)=\begin{cases}
\beta\left(u-1\right)+2 & \mbox{ for }0\le u<\frac{\beta-1}{\beta}\\
\beta\left(1-u\right) & \mbox{ for }\frac{\beta-1}{\beta}\le u\le1
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset

Performing a left-right flip on the side-tent brings it closer in form to
 the beta-transformation.
 The flipped version, replacing 
\begin_inset Formula $u\to1-u$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f_{\beta}(u)=\begin{cases}
\beta u & \mbox{ for }0\le u<\frac{1}{\beta}\\
2-\beta u & \mbox{ for }\frac{1}{\beta}\le u\le1
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The tent map (and the flipped tent) exhibits fixed points (periodic orbits;
 mode-locking) for the smaller values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

.
 These can be eliminated by shifting part of the tent downwards, so that
 the diagonal is never intersected.
 This suggests the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

sidetarp
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
