\begin_layout Section
Transfer operators
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Given any map from a space to itself, maping points to points, the pushfoward
 maps distributions to distributations.
 The pushfoward is a linear operator, called the transfer operator or the
 Ruelle–Frobenius–Perron operator.
 The spectrum of this operator, broken down into eigenfunctions and eigenvalues,
 can be used to understand the time evolution of a given density distribution.
 The invariant measure is an eigenstate of this operator, it is the eigenstate
 with eigenvalue one.
 There are other eigenstates; these are explored in this section.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Restricting to the unit interval, given an iterated map 
\begin_inset Formula $f:\left[0,1\right]\to\left[0,1\right]$
\end_inset

, the transfer operator acting on a distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho:\left[0,1\right]\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 is defined as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left[\mathcal{L}_{f}\rho\right]\left(y\right)=\sum_{x=f^{-1}(y)}\frac{\rho(x)}{\left|f^{\prime}(x)\right|}
\]

\end_inset

The next subsection gives an explicit expression for this, when 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is the 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

-transform.
 After that, a subsection reviewing the invariant measure, and then a discussion
 of some other eigenfunctions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

-shift Transfer Operator
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This text works primarily with the 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

-shift, instead of the more common 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

-transform.
 These two are more-or-less the same thing, differing only by scale factors,
 as given in eqn.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:xform-shift equivalence"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 The transfer operators are likewise only superficially different, being
 just rescalings of one-another; both are given below.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The transfer operator the beta-shift map 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{\beta}(x)$
\end_inset

 is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left[\mathcal{L}_{\beta}f\right]\left(y\right)=\begin{cases}
\frac{1}{\beta}\left[f\left(\frac{y}{\beta}\right)+f\left(\frac{y}{\beta}+\frac{1}{2}\right)\right] & \mbox{ for }0\le y\le\beta/2\\
0 & \mbox{ for }\beta/2<y\le1
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset

or, written more compactly
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left[\mathcal{L}_{\beta}f\right]\left(y\right)=\frac{1}{\beta}\left[f\left(\frac{y}{\beta}\right)+f\left(\frac{y}{\beta}+\frac{1}{2}\right)\right]\Theta\left(\frac{\beta}{2}-y\right)\label{eq:xfer oper}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\Theta$
\end_inset

 is the 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "Heaviside step function"
target "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Heaviside_step_function"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 The transfer operator for the beta-transform map 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{\beta}(x)$
\end_inset

 is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left[\mathcal{M}_{\beta}f\right]\left(y\right)=\frac{1}{\beta}\left[f\left(\frac{y}{\beta}\right)+f\left(\frac{y}{\beta}+\frac{1}{\beta}\right)\Theta\left(\beta-1-y\right)\right]
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The density distributions graphed in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Undershift-Density-Distribution"

\end_inset

 are those functions satisfying 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left[\mathcal{L}_{\beta}\mu\right]\left(y\right)=\mu\left(y\right)\label{eq:FP-eigenvector}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

That is, the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu\left(y\right)$
\end_inset

 satisfies 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mu\left(y\right)=\frac{1}{\beta}\left[\mu\left(\frac{y}{\beta}\right)+\mu\left(\frac{y}{\beta}+\frac{1}{2}\right)\right]\Theta\left(\frac{\beta}{2}-y\right)\label{eq:eigen-eqn}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Likewise, the Gelfond-Parry measure of eqn 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:invariant measure"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 satisfies
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left[\mathcal{M}_{\beta}\nu_{\beta}\right]\left(y\right)=\nu_{\beta}\left(y\right)
\]

\end_inset

Recall that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu\left(y\right)=\frac{2}{\beta}\nu_{\beta}\left(\frac{2y}{\beta}\right)\Theta\left(\frac{\beta}{2}-y\right)$
\end_inset

; the two invariant measures are just scaled copies of one-another.
 Both are normalized so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{0}^{1}\mu\left(y\right)dy=\int_{0}^{1}\nu_{\beta}\left(y\right)dy=1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Both of these invariant measures are the Ruelle-Frobenius-Perron (RFP) eigenfunc
tions of the corresponding operators, as they correspond to the largest
 eigenvalues of the transfer operators, in each case being the eigenvalue
 one.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
More generally, one is interested in characterizing the spectrum
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left[\mathcal{L}_{\beta}\rho\right]\left(y\right)=\lambda\rho\left(y\right)
\]

\end_inset

for eigenvalues 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\lambda\right|\le1$
\end_inset

 and eigenfunctions 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho\left(y\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Solving this equation requires choosing a space of functions in which to
 work.
 Natural choices include piece-wise continuous smooth functions (piece-wise
 polynomial functions), any of the Banach spaces, and in particular, the
 space of square-integrable functions.
 In general, the spectrum will be complex-valued: eigenvalues will be complex
 numbers.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If a distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho\left(y\right)$
\end_inset

 is nonozero on the interval 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\beta/2,1\right]$
\end_inset

, the operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{\beta}$
\end_inset

 will map it to one that is zero on this interval.
 Thus, it makes sense to restrict oneself to densities that are non-zero
 only on 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[0,\beta/2\right]$
\end_inset

.
 When this is done, eqn 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:xfer oper"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 has the slightly more convenient form
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left[\mathcal{L}_{\beta}f\right]\left(y\right)=\frac{1}{\beta}\left[f\left(\frac{y}{\beta}\right)\Theta\left(m_{0}-y\right)+f\left(\frac{y}{\beta}+\frac{1}{2}\right)\Theta\left(m_{1}-y\right)\right]
\]

\end_inset

with 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{0}=\beta/2$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{1}=\beta\left(\beta-1\right)/2=T_{\beta}\left(m_{0}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 It is always the case that 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{1}<m_{0}$
\end_inset

 and so the second term above vanished on the interval 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[m_{1},m_{0}\right]$
\end_inset

.
 This can be gainfully employed in a variety of settings; typically to write
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{\beta}f$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[m_{1},m_{0}\right]$
\end_inset

 as a simple rescaling of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{\beta}f$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[0,m_{1}\right]$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This equation can be treated as a recurrence relation; setting 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{\beta}f=f$
\end_inset

 gives the 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=1$
\end_inset

 eigenstate.
 Performing this recursion gives exactly the densities shown in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Undershift-Density-Distribution"

\end_inset

.
 Computationally, these are much cheaper to compute than trying to track
 a scattered cloud of points; the result is free of stochastic sampling
 noise.
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Computed in three places: rexfer.c reigen.c and complex.c
\end_layout

\end_inset

 This density is the Ruelle–Frobenius–Perron eigenstate; an explicit expression
 was given by Gelfond and by Parry, as described in the next section.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The Gelfond–Parry measure
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An explicit expression for the solution to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}_{\beta}\nu=\nu$
\end_inset

 was given by Gelfond
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Gelfond59"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and by Parry
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Parry60"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 It is the expression given by eqn 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:invariant measure"

\end_inset

.
 Unfortunately, I find the Russian original of Gelfond's article unreadable,
 and Parry's work, stemming from his PhD thesis, is not available online.
 Therefore, it is of some interest to provide a proof suitable for the current
 text.
 A generalization of this proof, stated in terms of a Borel algebra, is
 used in the subsequent section to construct general eigenfunctions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are two routes: either a direct verification that eqn 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:invariant measure"

\end_inset

 is correct, or a derivation of eqn 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:invariant measure"

\end_inset

 from geometric intuition.
 The direct verification is useful for practical purposes; the geometric
 construction, as a stretch-cut-stack map, provides insight.
 Both are given.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Direct verification
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A direct verification of correctness is done below, explicitly showing all
 steps in laborious detail.
 It's not at all difficult; just a bit hard on the eyes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As before, let 
\begin_inset Formula $t\left(x\right)\equiv t_{\beta}\left(x\right)=\beta x\mod1$
\end_inset

 be the 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

-transformation of eqn 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:beta transform"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $t^{n}\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 the iterated transformation.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\Theta(x)$
\end_inset

 be the Heaviside step function as always, and to keep notation brief, let
 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{n}\equiv t^{n}\left(1\right)$
\end_inset

.
 The Gelfond-Parry measure is then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\nu\left(y\right)=\frac{1}{F}\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}\frac{\Theta\left(t_{n}-y\right)}{\beta^{n}}
\]

\end_inset

where the normalization 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
F=\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}\frac{t_{n}}{\beta^{n}}
\]

\end_inset

The transfer operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 for the beta-transformation is slightly more convenient to work with than
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}$
\end_inset

 for this particular case.
 It is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left[\mathcal{M}f\right]\left(y\right)=\frac{1}{\beta}\left[f\left(\frac{y}{\beta}\right)+f\left(\frac{y+1}{\beta}\right)\Theta\left(\beta-1-y\right)\right]
\]

\end_inset

and we wish to verify that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}\nu=\nu$
\end_inset

.
 Plugging in directly,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
P=\nu\left(\frac{y}{\beta}\right) & +\nu\left(\frac{y+1}{\beta}\right)\Theta\left(\beta-1-y\right)=\\
 & =\frac{1}{F}\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}\frac{1}{\beta^{n}}\left(\Theta\left(t_{n}-\frac{y}{\beta}\right)+\Theta\left(t_{n}-\frac{y+1}{\beta}\right)\Theta\left(\beta-1-y\right)\right)\\
 & =\frac{1}{F}\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}\frac{1}{\beta^{n}}\left(\Theta\left(\beta t_{n}-y\right)+\Theta\left(\beta t_{n}-1-y\right)\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

The second line follows from the first, since 
\begin_inset Formula $\Theta\left(ax\right)=\Theta\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 for all constants 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

, and the 
\begin_inset Formula $\Theta\left(\beta-1-y\right)$
\end_inset

 can be safely dropped, since 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{n}\le1$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
 These terms simplify, depending on whether 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{n}$
\end_inset

 is small or large.
 Explicitly, one has
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\Theta\left(\beta t_{n}-1-y\right)=0 & \mbox{ if }\beta t_{n}-1<0\\
\Theta\left(\beta t_{n}-y\right)=1 & \mbox{ if }\beta t_{n}-1>0
\end{align*}

\end_inset

and so
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P=\frac{1}{F}\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}\frac{1}{\beta^{n}}\left(\Theta\left(1-\beta t_{n}\right)\Theta\left(\beta t_{n}-y\right)+\Theta\left(\beta t_{n}-1\right)\left(1+\Theta\left(\beta t_{n}-1-y\right)\right)\right)
\]

\end_inset

These can be collapsed by noting that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\beta t_{n}=t_{n+1} & \mbox{ if }\beta t_{n}-1<0\\
\beta t_{n}-1=t_{n+1} & \mbox{ if }\beta t_{n}-1>0
\end{align*}

\end_inset

and so
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
P & =\frac{1}{F}\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}\frac{1}{\beta^{n}}\left(\Theta\left(1-\beta t_{n}\right)\Theta\left(t_{n+1}-y\right)+\Theta\left(\beta t_{n}-1\right)\left(1+\Theta\left(t_{n+1}-y\right)\right)\right)\\
 & =\frac{1}{F}\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}\frac{1}{\beta^{n}}\left(\Theta\left(t_{n+1}-y\right)\left[\Theta\left(1-\beta t_{n}\right)+\Theta\left(\beta t_{n}-1\right)\right]+\Theta\left(\beta t_{n}-1\right)\right)\\
 & =\frac{1}{F}\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}\frac{1}{\beta^{n}}\left(\Theta\left(t_{n+1}-y\right)+\Theta\left(\beta t_{n}-1\right)\right)\\
 & =\beta\nu\left(y\right)-\frac{\beta}{F}+\frac{1}{F}\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}\frac{\Theta\left(\beta t_{n}-1\right)}{\beta^{n}}\\
 & =\beta\nu\left(y\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

The last sum on the right is just the 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

-expansion for 1.
 That is, the 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

-expansion of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x=\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}\frac{\Theta\left(\beta t^{n}\left(x\right)-1\right)}{\beta^{n+1}}
\]

\end_inset

This is just eqn 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:shift series"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 written in a different way (making use of the equivalence 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:xform-shift equivalence"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $P=\beta\nu\left(y\right)$
\end_inset

 and so 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}\nu=\nu$
\end_inset

 as claimed.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Stretch–Cut–Stack Map
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The measure can be geometrically constructed and intuitively understood
 as the result of the repeated application of a bakers-map-style stretch
 and squash operation.
 The idea is to iterate 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{n+1}=\mathcal{M}_{\beta}\nu_{n}$
\end_inset

, starting with 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{0}=1$
\end_inset

 and then take the limit 
\begin_inset Formula $n\to\infty$
\end_inset

; the result is 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{n}\to\nu$
\end_inset

 in the limit, given as above.
 The basic stretch-cut-stack operation provides intuition as to why 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

 is invariant.
 The proof that it converges as desired is nearly identical to the (shorter)
 proof above.
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
This section has more details in the diary.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider a first approximation that 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{0}$
\end_inset

 is constant on the interval 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[0,1\right]$
\end_inset

, so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{0}\left(y\right)=1$
\end_inset

.
 The operation of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 acting on this is to stretch it out to the interval 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[0,\beta\right]$
\end_inset

, chop off the 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[1,\beta\right]$
\end_inset

 part, move it to 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[0,\beta-1\right]$
\end_inset

, stack it on top, thus doubling the density in this region.
 The doubling, though, is partly counteracted by the stretching, which thins
 out the density to 
\begin_inset Formula $1/\beta$
\end_inset

 uniformly over the entire interval 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[0,\beta\right]$
\end_inset

.
 This operation preserves the grand-total measure on the unit interval.
 Writing 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta-1=t_{1}=t\left(t_{0}\right)=t\left(1\right)$
\end_inset

 for the first iterate of the endpoint 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{0}=1$
\end_inset

, this stretch, cut and stack operation should result in 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\nu_{1}\left(y\right)=\begin{cases}
\frac{2}{\beta} & \mbox{for }y\in\left[0,t_{1}\right]\\
\frac{1}{\beta} & \mbox{for }y\in\left[t_{1},t_{0}\right]
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset

The stretch–cut–stack operation is the intuitive, geometrical explanation
 for obtaining the first iterate.
 The same result is obtained algebraically, by writing 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{1}=\mathcal{M}\nu_{0}$
\end_inset

 and then plugging and chugging:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\nu_{1}\left(y\right)=\frac{1}{\beta}\left[1+\Theta\left(t_{1}-y\right)\right]
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The derivation of a recursive formula for 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{n}$
\end_inset

 follows along the line of the algebraic proof given in the previous section,
 this time, limiting the sums to finite order.
 The general form is 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\nu_{n}=\rho_{n}-\sum_{k=0}^{n-1}c_{n-k}\nu_{k}
\]

\end_inset

which is preserved under iteration as 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{n+1}=\mathcal{M}\nu_{n}$
\end_inset

.
 The two parts are 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{n}$
\end_inset

 defined as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\rho_{n}=\sum_{k=0}^{n}\frac{1}{\beta^{k}}\Theta\left(t_{k}-y\right)
\]

\end_inset

This converges, up to overall normalization, to the invariant measure: 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{n}\to F\nu$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 the normalization constant from before.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{n}$
\end_inset

 are constants, defined as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
c_{n}=1-\sum_{k=0}^{n-1}\frac{\Theta\left(\beta t_{k}-1\right)}{\beta^{k+1}}\label{eq:iteration const}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The sum in 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{n}$
\end_inset

 is a partial 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

-expansion for 1.
 Each term can be recognized as a bit from the bit-expansion:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Theta\left(\beta t_{k}-1\right)=d_{n}\left(\frac{1}{2}\right)=k_{n}\left(\frac{\beta}{2}\right)=\varepsilon_{n}\left(\frac{1}{\beta}\right)
\]

\end_inset

with 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{n}$
\end_inset

 as defined in eqn 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:down-bits"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{n}$
\end_inset

 defined as in eqn 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Gelfond-Parry digits"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{n}$
\end_inset

 as in eqn 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:rescaled-bitseq"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 (apologies for the variety of notations; each is 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

natural
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in a specific context.) The 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

-expansion of a real number 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is as given in eqn 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:shift series"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 In the present context, this is the expansion for 
\begin_inset Formula $x=\beta/2$
\end_inset

, or, after rescaling, the expansion for 
\begin_inset Formula $x=1$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
1=\sum_{k=0}^{\infty}\frac{\Theta\left(\beta t_{k}-1\right)}{\beta^{k+1}}
\]

\end_inset

Thus, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|c_{n}\right|<\beta^{-n+1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{n}\to0$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $n\to\infty$
\end_inset

.
 The sum in 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{n}$
\end_inset

 is a partial 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

-expansion for 1.
 Thus, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|c_{n}\right|<\beta^{-n+1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{n}\to0$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $n\to\infty$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Each iteration preserves the measure; this is built into the construction.
 That is, 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{0}^{1}\nu_{n}\left(y\right)dy=1$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
 Plugging through gives a curious identity:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
1=\int_{0}^{1}\nu_{n}\left(y\right)dy=\sum_{k=0}^{n}\frac{t_{k}}{\beta^{k}}-\sum_{k=1}^{n}c_{k}
\]

\end_inset

which holds for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
 This is readily verified by further plugging through; the underlying identity
 is that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
t_{n}=\beta^{n}c_{n}
\]

\end_inset

This follows by noticing that each 
\begin_inset Formula $\Theta\left(\beta t_{k}-1\right)$
\end_inset

 records a decision to decrement, or not, the product 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta t_{k}$
\end_inset

 occurring in the iteration 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{k+1}=\beta t_{k}\mod1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Gelfond–Parry normalization was the 
\begin_inset Formula $n\to\infty$
\end_inset

 limit of the first sum: 
\begin_inset Formula $F=\sum_{k=0}^{\infty}\beta^{-k}t_{k}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Stacking Generic Functions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A slightly different calculation results if one works with an an arbitrary
 function 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{0}\left(y\right)$
\end_inset

.
 The iteration to obtain 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{n}=\mathcal{M}^{n}\nu_{0}$
\end_inset

 proceeds much as before, with only minor modifications needed to obtain
 the general form.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The trick is to track two distinct travellers: one that travels with 
\begin_inset Formula $\Theta\left(t_{k}-y\right)$
\end_inset

 and another that travels with the bitsequence 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{k}=\Theta\left(\beta t_{k}-1\right)$
\end_inset

.
 The general solution has the form
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\nu_{n}\left(y\right) & =a_{n}\left(y\right)+\sum_{k=1}^{n}h_{nk}\left(y\right)\Theta\left(t_{k}-y\right)\\
a_{n}\left(y\right) & =\sum_{k=0}^{n-1}b_{k}e_{nk}\left(y\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

The functions 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{nk}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{nk}$
\end_inset

 can be solved for recursively; the recursive relations are simple enough
 that they can be rolled up as series summations.
 These are given by
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
h_{nk}\left(y\right) & =\frac{1}{\beta^{k}}a_{n-k}\left(t_{1}-\frac{\beta t_{k}-1}{\beta^{k}}+\frac{y}{\beta^{k}}\right)\quad\mbox{ for }n\ge k
\end{align*}

\end_inset

which express 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{nk}$
\end_inset

 in terms of the function 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{n}$
\end_inset

.
 This is given as a recursive series, obtained by iterating
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
e_{nk}\left(y\right)=\frac{1}{\beta^{n}}\left[\nu_{0}\left(1-\frac{t_{k}}{\beta^{k}}+\frac{y}{\beta^{n}}\right)+\Theta\left(k\right)\sum_{m=1}^{n-k-1}\beta^{m}a_{m}\left(t_{1}-\frac{\beta t_{k}-1}{\beta^{k}}+\frac{\beta^{m}y}{\beta^{n}}\right)\right]
\]

\end_inset

The starting point for iteration is 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{0}=\nu_{0}$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Above works great, verifies against earlier forms.
 Look at check/unstack.c and unstack.gplot for implementation.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The function 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{n}$
\end_inset

 is polynomial if 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{0}$
\end_inset

 is, and of the same degree; 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{n}$
\end_inset

 is analytic, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{0}$
\end_inset

 is, and so on.
 The function 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{nk}$
\end_inset

 is likewise, on the domain 
\begin_inset Formula $0\le y\le t_{k}$
\end_inset

; the discontinuities in 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{n}$
\end_inset

 are entirely due to the 
\begin_inset Formula $\Theta\left(t_{k}-y\right)$
\end_inset

 term.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The proper calculation of the 
\begin_inset Formula $n\to\infty$
\end_inset

 limit of 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{n}$
\end_inset

 remains a mystery.
 This is the primary obstacle to constructing general eigenfunctions from
 this series.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Verification
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{0}=1$
\end_inset

, all three functions 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{n},e_{nk}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{nk}$
\end_inset

 become constants.
 In this case, 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{n}\to1/F$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $n\to\infty$
\end_inset

, with 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 the normalization constant as before.
 Defining 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{n}=\beta^{n}a_{n}$
\end_inset

, the recursion relation takes the curious form 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\alpha_{n}=1+\sum_{k=1}^{n-1}b_{k}\sum_{m=0}^{n-k-1}\alpha_{m}
\]

\end_inset

This is an integer sequence: each 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{n}$
\end_inset

 is an integer, starting with 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{0}=\alpha_{1}=1$
\end_inset

.
 This has the form of a generalized Fibonacci sequence.
 Denote the partial sum as 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{i}=\sum_{m=0}^{i}\alpha_{m}$
\end_inset

.
 This implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{i}=s_{i}-s_{i-1}$
\end_inset

 and so
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\alpha_{n} & =1+b_{1}s_{n-2}+b_{2}s_{n-3}+\cdots\\
s_{n} & =1+s_{n-1}+b_{1}s_{n-2}+b_{2}s_{n-3}+\cdots
\end{align*}

\end_inset

If the orbit is of finite length 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, so that 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{k}=0$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $k>p$
\end_inset

, then this can be recast directly into generalized Fibonacci form, by defining
 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{n}=s_{n}+\sum_{k=1}^{p}b_{k}$
\end_inset

.
 The recursion relation is then
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f_{n}=f_{n-1}+b_{1}f_{n-2}+\cdots+b_{p}f_{n-p}
\]

\end_inset

For example, the orbit generated by 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta=\varphi=1.618\cdots$
\end_inset

 the golden mean has 
\begin_inset Formula $p=1,b_{1}=1$
\end_inset

 and the sequence is 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{m}=1,1,2,3,5,8,13,\cdots$
\end_inset

.
 Finite orbits and generalized Fibonacci sequences will be treated at length
 in the next chapter.
 One of the interesting properties is that 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta=\lim_{n\to\infty}f_{n}/f_{n-1}$
\end_inset

 holds in the general case, and not just for the golden mean.
 The bitsequences are self-describing; this is byproduct from the identity
 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta=\sum_{k=0}^{\infty}b_{k}\beta^{-k}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Analytic Gelfond-Parry function
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Rotated-Renyi-Parry-function"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The steps performed above can be repeated verbatim for a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

rotated
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

coherent
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 function
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\nu_{\beta;z}\left(y\right)=\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}z^{n}\frac{\Theta\left(t_{n}-y\right)}{\beta^{n}}\label{eq:generalized-eigenfunction}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

for a given complex-valued 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

.
 No changes are required, and the result can be read off directly:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\left[\mathcal{M}\nu_{\beta;z}\right]\left(y\right) & =\frac{\nu_{\beta;z}\left(y\right)}{z}-\frac{1}{z}+\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}z^{n}\frac{\Theta\left(\beta t_{n}-1\right)}{\beta^{n+1}}\\
 & =\frac{\nu_{\beta;z}\left(y\right)}{z}+C\left(\beta;z\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

with 
\begin_inset Formula $C\left(\beta;z\right)$
\end_inset

 being a constant independent of 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

.
 If there are values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 and/or 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 at which 
\begin_inset Formula $C\left(\beta;z\right)=0$
\end_inset

, then this becomes the eigenequation for 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The eigenfunction for 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}$
\end_inset

 is the same, up to rescaling of 
\begin_inset Formula $y\mapsto\beta x/2$
\end_inset

.
 Recycling notation slightly, write
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
v_{\beta;z}\left(x\right)=\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}\frac{d_{n}\left(x\right)}{\beta^{n}}z^{n}\label{eq:coherent-first-order}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where the 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{n}\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 are exactly the same digits as defined by Parry, just rescaled for the
 beta-shift.
 That is, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
d_{n}\left(x\right)=\varepsilon_{n}\left(\frac{2x}{\beta}\right)=\Theta\left(\frac{\beta}{2}t_{n}-x\right)=\Theta\left(T^{n}\left(\frac{\beta}{2}\right)-x\right)=\begin{cases}
1 & \mbox{if }x<T^{n}\left(\frac{\beta}{2}\right)\\
0 & \mbox{otherwise}
\end{cases}\label{eq:rescaled-bitseq}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 the beta-shift map of eqn 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:downshift"

\end_inset

 and eqn 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:xform-shift equivalence"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 is used.
 The iterated end-point becomes the iterated midpoint:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
t^{n}\left(1\right)=\frac{2}{\beta}T^{n}\left(\frac{\beta}{2}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Holding both 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 fixed, the summation is clearly convergent (and holomorphic in 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

) for complex numbers 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 within the disk 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|z\right|<\beta$
\end_inset

.
 The eigenequation has the same form:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left[\mathcal{L}_{\beta}v_{\beta;z}\right]\left(x\right)=\frac{1}{z}v_{\beta;z}\left(x\right)+C\left(\beta;z\right)
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $C\left(\beta;z\right)$
\end_inset

 is a constant independent of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 Numeric verification reveals we were a bit glib: 
\begin_inset Formula $C\left(\beta;z\right)$
\end_inset

 is a constant for 
\begin_inset Formula $x\le\beta/2$
\end_inset

 and is zero otherwise! (This is normal; 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}$
\end_inset

 was defined in such a way that it is always exactly zero for 
\begin_inset Formula $x>\beta/2$
\end_inset

.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The interesting limit is where 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|z\right|\to\beta$
\end_inset

 and so its convenient to re-express 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 in terms of 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta=z/\beta$
\end_inset

, so that everything is mapped to the unit disk.
 With some rearrangements, one obtains
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
E\left(\beta;\zeta\right)\equiv\zeta\beta C\left(\beta;\zeta\beta\right)=-1+\zeta\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}\zeta^{n}d_{n}\left(\frac{1}{2}\right)\label{eq:holomorphic-disk}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Given that 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{n}\left(1/2\right)=\Theta\left(\beta t_{n}-1\right)$
\end_inset

, the above can be recognized as the rotated/coherent form of eqn 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:iteration const"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 in the 
\begin_inset Formula $n\to\infty$
\end_inset

 limit.
 The primary task is to characterize the zeros of 
\begin_inset Formula $E\left(\beta;\zeta\right)$
\end_inset

.
 This is a straight-forward sum to examine numerically; results will be
 presented in the section after the next.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Analytic ergodics
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This section proposes that the entire 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

-subshift can be tied together with a single holomorphic equation.
 The holomorphic equation effectively provides a continuum (
\emph on
i.e.

\emph default
 uncountable number) of distinct relationships between different parts of
 the subshift.
 This can be interpreted either as a form of interaction across the subshift,
 or as a kind of mixing.
 Given the nature of the relationship, the moniker of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

fundamental theorem of analytic ergodics
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is an amusing name to assign to the result.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The constant term can be independently derived through a different set of
 manipulations.
 Explicitly plugging in eqn 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:coherent-first-order"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 into the transfer operator yields
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
C\left(\beta;z\right)= & \left[\mathcal{L}_{\beta}v_{\beta;z}\right]\left(y\right)-\frac{v_{\beta;z}\left(y\right)}{z}\\
= & \sum_{n=0}^{\infty}\frac{z^{n}}{\beta^{n}}\left[\frac{1}{\beta}\left[d_{n}\left(\frac{y}{\beta}\right)+d_{n}\left(\frac{y}{\beta}+\frac{1}{2}\right)\right]\Theta\left(\frac{\beta}{2}-y\right)-\frac{1}{z}d_{n}\left(y\right)\right]
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Replacing 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta=z/\beta$
\end_inset

 gives
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
E\left(\beta;\zeta\right)= & \zeta\beta C\left(\beta;\zeta\beta\right)\\
= & \sum_{n=0}^{\infty}\zeta^{n}\left[\zeta\left[d_{n}\left(\frac{y}{\beta}\right)+d_{n}\left(\frac{y}{\beta}+\frac{1}{2}\right)\right]\Theta\left(\frac{\beta}{2}-y\right)-d_{n}\left(y\right)\right]
\end{align*}

\end_inset

This is holomorphic on the unit disk 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\zeta\right|<1$
\end_inset

, as each individual 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{n}$
\end_inset

 is either zero or one; there won't be any poles inside the unit disk.
 Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{n}\left(y\right)=0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $y>\beta/2$
\end_inset

, and so one may pull out the step function to write 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
E\left(\beta;\zeta\right)=\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}\zeta^{n}\left[\zeta d_{n}\left(\frac{y}{\beta}\right)+\zeta d_{n}\left(\frac{y}{\beta}+\frac{1}{2}\right)-d_{n}\left(y\right)\right]\Theta\left(\frac{\beta}{2}-y\right)
\]

\end_inset

confirming the earlier observation that 
\begin_inset Formula $E\left(\beta;\zeta\right)$
\end_inset

 vanishes for all 
\begin_inset Formula $y>\beta/2$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The bottom equation holds without assuming that 
\begin_inset Formula $E\left(\beta;\zeta\right)$
\end_inset

 is independent of 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

.
 However, we've already proven that it is; and so a simplified expression
 can be given simply by picking a specific 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

.
 Setting 
\begin_inset Formula $y=0$
\end_inset

, noting that 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{n}\left(0\right)=1$
\end_inset

 and canceling terms, one obtains eqn.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:holomorphic-disk"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 again.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Staring at the right-hand side of the sum above, it is hardly obvious that
 it should be independent of 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

.
 In a certain sense, this is not 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

one equation
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, this holds for a continuum of 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

, for all 
\begin_inset Formula $0\le y\le1$
\end_inset

.
 It is an analytic equation tying together the entire subshift.
 For each distinct 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

, it singles out three completely different bit-sequences out of the subshift,
 and ties them together.
 It is a form of mixing.
 Alternately, a form of interaction: the bit-sequences are not independent
 of one-another; they interact.
 This section attempts to make these notions more precise.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The tying-together of seemingly unrelated sequences seems somehow terribly
 important.
 It is amusing to suggest that this is a kind of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

fundamental theorem of analytic ergodics
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For such a claim, it is worth discussing the meaning at length, taking the
 effort to be exceptionally precise and verbose, perhaps a bit repetitive.
 Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:downshift"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 defined a map, the 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

-shift.
 Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:down-bits"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 defined a bit-sequence, the 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

-expansion of a real number 
\begin_inset Formula $0\le x\le1$
\end_inset

, where equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:shift series"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 is the definition of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

-expansion.
 The set of all such bit-sequences defines the shift.
 To emphasize this point, its best to compare side-by-side.
 Copying equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:down-bits"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, one bitsequence records the orbit of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 relative to the modpoint: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
k_{n}\left(x\right)=\begin{cases}
0 & \mbox{ if }0\le T_{\beta}^{n}(x)<\frac{1}{2}\\
1 & \mbox{ if }\frac{1}{2}\le T_{\beta}^{n}(x)\le1
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset

 while a different bitsequence records the orbit of the midpoint, relative
 to 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
d_{n}\left(x\right)=\begin{cases}
1 & \mbox{if }x<T^{n}\left(\frac{\beta}{2}\right)=T^{n+1}\left(\frac{1}{2}\right)\\
0 & \mbox{otherwise}
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset

The iterations are running in opposite directions; this is as appropriate,
 since the the transfer operator was a push-forward.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is useful to return to the language of sigma algebras and cylinder sets,
 as opposed to point dynamics.
 Recall that the Borel algebra 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}$
\end_inset

 was defined as the sigma algebra, the collection of all cylinder sets in
 the product topology of 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ 0,1\right\} ^{\omega}$
\end_inset

.
 A subshift is a subset 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{S}\subset\mathcal{B}$
\end_inset

 together with a map 
\begin_inset Formula $T:\mathcal{S}\to\mathcal{S}$
\end_inset

 that lops off the leading symbol of a given cylinder set but otherwise
 preserves the subshift: 
\begin_inset Formula $T\mathcal{S}=\mathcal{S}$
\end_inset

.
 The inverted map 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{-1}$
\end_inset

 is a pushforward, in that it defines the transfer operator, a linear operator
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{T}:\mathcal{F\to\mathcal{F}}$
\end_inset

 on the space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 of all functions 
\begin_inset Formula $f:\mathcal{S}\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

; explicitly, it is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{T}:f\mapsto f\circ T^{-1}$
\end_inset

.
 Insofar as the 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{n}$
\end_inset

 arose in the exploration of the transfer operator, it is not surprising
 that the shift is acting 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

backwards
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The problem with the language of point dynamics is that one cannot meaningfully
 write 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{-n}\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 for a real number, a point 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, at least, not without severe contortions that lead back to the Borel algebra.
 Not for lack of trying; the 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{-n}\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 is called the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Julia set
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (to order 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

) of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

: it is the preimage, the set of all points that, when iterated, converge
 onto 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Can the analytic relation be restated in terms of cylinder sets? Yes, and
 it follows in a fairly natural way.
 The first step is to extend 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{n}$
\end_inset

 to a map 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{n}:\mathcal{S}\to\left[0,1\right]$
\end_inset

 into the unit interval, as opposed to being a single bit.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu:\mathcal{B}\to\left[0,1\right]$
\end_inset

 be the canonical Bernoulli measure.
 Using the Bernoulli mapping 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:homomorphism"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, the interval 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[0,T^{n}\left(\beta/2\right)\right]$
\end_inset

 maps to some cylinder; call it 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta_{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Then, given some cylinder 
\begin_inset Formula $A\in\mathcal{S}$
\end_inset

, define
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
d_{n}\left(A\right)=\mu\left(A\cap\Delta_{n}\right)
\]

\end_inset

The rotated (pre-)measure is extended likewise: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\nu\left(A\right)=\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}\zeta^{n}d_{n}\left(A\right)
\]

\end_inset

with 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta=z/\beta$
\end_inset

 as before, recovering the Parry measure by setting 
\begin_inset Formula $z=1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Parry measure should be invariant under the action of 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{-1}:\mathcal{S}\to\mathcal{S}$
\end_inset

, and otherwise yield eqn 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:holomorphic-disk"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 Let's check.
 The proof will mirror the one of the previous section.
 Again, it is convenient to use the 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

-transform 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{\beta}$
\end_inset

 instead of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

-shift 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{\beta}$
\end_inset

.
 This is primarily a conceptual convenience; the subshift is more easily
 visualized in terms of the mod 1 map.
 Otherwise, the same notation is used, but rescaled, so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta_{n}$
\end_inset

 is the cylinder corresponding to the interval 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[0,t^{n}\left(1\right)\right]$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Recall that for every 
\begin_inset Formula $A\in\mathcal{S}$
\end_inset

 and every 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in A$
\end_inset

, one will find that 
\begin_inset Formula $y/\beta\in t^{-1}\left(A\right)$
\end_inset

 and, whenever 
\begin_inset Formula $y\le\beta-1$
\end_inset

 that also 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(y+1\right)/\beta\in t^{-1}\left(A\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, 
\begin_inset Formula $t^{-1}\left(A\right)$
\end_inset

 naturally splits into two parts: the cylinder that maps to 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[0,1/\beta\right]$
\end_inset

, call it 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

, and the complement 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{D}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The pushfoward action is then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\nu\left(t^{-1}\left(A\right)\right)= & \sum_{n=0}^{\infty}\zeta^{n}\mu\left(\Delta_{n}\cap t^{-1}\left(A\right)\right)\\
= & \sum_{n=0}^{\infty}\zeta^{n}\left[\mu\left(\Delta_{n}\cap D\cap t^{-1}\left(A\right)\right)+\mu\left(\Delta_{n}\cap\overline{D}\cap t^{-1}\left(A\right)\right)\right]
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Two distinct cases emerge.
 When 
\begin_inset Formula $t^{n}\left(1\right)<1/\beta$
\end_inset

 then one has that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta_{n}\cap\overline{D}=\varnothing$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, the second term can be written as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mu\left(\Delta_{n}\cap\overline{D}\cap t^{-1}\left(A\right)\right) & =\Theta\left(t_{n}-\frac{1}{\beta}\right)\mu\left(\Delta_{n}\cap\overline{D}\cap t^{-1}\left(A\right)\right)\\
 & =\Theta\left(t_{n}-\frac{1}{\beta}\right)\frac{1}{\beta}\mu\left(\Delta_{n+1}\cap A\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where the second line follows from the first by linearity, and that 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{D}$
\end_inset

 selected out one of the two branches of 
\begin_inset Formula $t^{-1}\left(A\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Meanwhile, when 
\begin_inset Formula $t^{n}\left(1\right)>1/\beta$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $D\subset\Delta_{n}$
\end_inset

 so that 
\begin_inset Formula $D\cap\Delta_{n}=D$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, the first term splits into two: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\Theta\left(t_{n}-\frac{1}{\beta}\right)\mu\left(\Delta_{n}\cap D\cap t^{-1}\left(A\right)\right) & =\Theta\left(t_{n}-\frac{1}{\beta}\right)\mu\left(D\cap t^{-1}\left(A\right)\right)\\
 & =\Theta\left(t_{n}-\frac{1}{\beta}\right)\frac{1}{\beta}\mu\left(A\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

while
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Theta\left(\frac{1}{\beta}-t_{n}\right)\mu\left(\Delta_{n}\cap D\cap t^{-1}\left(A\right)\right)=\Theta\left(\frac{1}{\beta}-t_{n}\right)\frac{1}{\beta}\mu\left(\Delta_{n+1}\cap A\right)
\]

\end_inset

Reassembling these pieces and making use of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta_{0}\cap A=A$
\end_inset

 one gets
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\nu\left(t^{-1}\left(A\right)\right) & =\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}\frac{\zeta^{n}}{\beta}\left[\mu\left(A\right)\Theta\left(t_{n}-\frac{1}{\beta}\right)+\mu\left(\Delta_{n+1}\cap A\right)\right]\\
 & =\frac{1}{z}\nu\left(A\right)-\frac{\mu\left(A\right)}{z}+\mu\left(A\right)\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}\frac{\zeta^{n}}{\beta}\Theta\left(t_{n}-\frac{1}{\beta}\right)\\
 & =\frac{1}{z}\nu\left(A\right)+\frac{\mu\left(A\right)}{z}E\left(\beta;z\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

with the constant term as before, in eqn 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:holomorphic-disk"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
E\left(\beta;z\right) & =-1+\zeta\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}\zeta^{n}\Theta\left(t_{n}-\frac{1}{\beta}\right)\\
 & =-1+\zeta\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}\zeta^{n}d_{n}\left(\frac{1}{2}\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

As before, one has for 
\begin_inset Formula $z=1$
\end_inset

 that 
\begin_inset Formula $E\left(\beta;1\right)=0$
\end_inset

 and so 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu\circ t^{-1}=\nu$
\end_inset

 is indeed the measure invariant under 
\begin_inset Formula $t^{-1}$
\end_inset

.
 Other eigenvalues can be found for those values of 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 for which 
\begin_inset Formula $E\left(\beta;z\right)=0$
\end_inset

.
 The task at hand is then to characterize 
\begin_inset Formula $E\left(\beta;z\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

