\begin_layout Standard
This appears to be Sloane's OEIS A001037 which has a number of known relationshi
ps to roots of unity, Lyndon words, and the number of orbits in the tent
 map.
 The trouble spots are the positive real roots of polynomials of the form
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p_{\left\{ b_{k}\right\} }\left(\beta\right)=\beta^{\nu}-\beta^{\nu-1}-b_{1}\beta^{\nu-2}-b_{2}\beta^{\nu-3}-\cdots-1=0
\]

\end_inset

with the 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ b_{k}\right\} $
\end_inset

 being certain binary bit sequences.
 There is just one such (positive, real) root for each such polynomial.
 These polynomials are relatively prime, in the sense that a bit-sequence
 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{k}$
\end_inset

 is disallowed if it has the same root as some lower-order polynomial.
 For example, 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta^{4}-\beta^{3}-\beta-1$
\end_inset

 is disallowed; it has the same root as 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta^{2}-\beta-1$
\end_inset

.
 Equivalently, the quadratic is a factor of the quartic; the quartic is
 not relatively prime with respect to the quadratic.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The reason for the appearance of the necklace-counting function is straightforwa
rd: it is counting the number of distinct orbits of a given length.
 An orbit of length 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

 is, by definition, a point 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $x=T_{\beta}^{\nu}\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Such an orbit generates a binary string, of length 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

 corresponding to whether 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{\beta}^{j}\left(x\right)<1/2$
\end_inset

 is true or not.
 A cyclic permutation of such a string still corresponds to the same orbit;
 a reversed permutation does not: thus, it is a necklace without reversal.
 The necklace-counting function gives the number of distinct, unique orbits
 of a given length that cannot be factored into shorter orbits.
 The beta transformation has the property that every possible orbit does
 occur; none are prohibited.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A recurring point of confusion is that the bit-string defining the polynomial
 is not a necklace; it cannot be rotated.
 Each bit-string corresponds to a unique polynomial, having roots that differ
 from those of other polynomials.
 The polynomials also have a canonical order, fixed as the integer that
 corresponds to the bit-string; they cannot be reordered.
 Ideas such as Lyndon words apply to the orbits, but not to the defining
 polynomials.
 The ordering of the polynomials is 
\emph on
not
\emph default
 the lexicographic ordering of the Lyndon words, and cannot be brought into
 this order.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The values of 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{n}$
\end_inset

 are given explicitly by Moreau's necklace-counting function
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
M_{n}=\frac{1}{n}\sum_{d|n}2^{d}\mu\left(\frac{n}{d}\right)
\]

\end_inset

where the sum runs over all integers 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 that divide 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 is the Möbius function.
 The generating function is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{t}{\frac{1}{2}-t}=\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}nM_{n}\frac{t^{n}}{1-t^{n}}
\]

\end_inset

which has a radius of convergence of 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|t\right|<1/2$
\end_inset

.
 For large 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

, the asymptotic behavior can be trivially deduced from the defining sum:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
M_{n}=\frac{2^{n}}{n}-\mathcal{O}\left(\frac{2^{n/2}}{n}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The above counting function is for necklaces with only two colors.
 In general, one can have necklaces with 3 or more colors; can that happen
 here? Yes, of course: if one considers the general 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

-transform for 
\begin_inset Formula $2<\beta$
\end_inset

, then, in general, it can be taken as a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

kneading transform
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\lceil \beta\right\rceil $
\end_inset

 branches or folds in it.
 The analogous trouble-spots again appear, and they can appear after an
 arbitrary finite-length orbit.
 Insofar as they correspond to periodic orbits, they are necessarily counted
 by the necklace-counting function.
 That is, one must consider all possible strings of 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\lceil \beta\right\rceil $
\end_inset

 letters, modulo a cyclic permutation: this is the very definition of a
 necklace (or 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

circular word
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

).
 The number of such necklaces is given by the necklace-counting function.
 Each such orbit is necessarily represented by a Lyndon word, which is a
 representative of the conjugacy class of the orbit.
\end_layout

