\begin_layout Standard
The 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

trouble spots
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 occur whenever the 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

'th iterate 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{k}=T_{\beta}^{k}\left(m_{0}\right)$
\end_inset

 of the midpoint 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{0}=\beta/2$
\end_inset

 lands on the starting midpoint 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{k}=m_{0}$
\end_inset

; alternately, when 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{k-1}=1/2$
\end_inset

.
 Because of the piece-wise linear form of 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{\beta}$
\end_inset

, the 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

'th iterate will be a piece-wise collection of polynomials, each of order
 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

, each of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{\left\{ b_{k}\right\} }\left(\beta\right)$
\end_inset

.
 These must be arranged such that 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{\left\{ b_{k}\right\} }\left(\beta\right)=0$
\end_inset

 at each discontinuity, as illustrated in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Location-of-Midpoints"

\end_inset

.
 This constrains the polynomials that can appear; it constrains the possible
 coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ b_{k}\right\} $
\end_inset

; not all bit-sequences appear.
 The sequences that do appear encode the orbit of the mid-point; see below.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The table below explicitly shows the polynomials for the first few orders.
 A polynomial is included in the table if it is an iterate of a previous
 polynomial, and if it's real root is bracketed by the roots of the earlier
 iterates.
 Adopting an ordinal numbering, 
\begin_inset Formula $\ensuremath{p_{n}\left(\beta\right)}$
\end_inset

 must have the form
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
p_{n}\left(\beta\right)=\begin{cases}
\beta\left(p_{n/2}\left(\beta\right)+1\right)-1 & \mbox{ for \ensuremath{n} even }\\
\beta p_{\left(n-1\right)/2}\left(\beta\right)-1 & \mbox{ for \ensuremath{n} odd }
\end{cases}\label{eq:polynomial recursion}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

This recursion terminates at 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{0}\left(\beta\right)=\beta-1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The positive real root 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{n}$
\end_inset

 satisfying 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{n}\left(r_{n}\right)=0$
\end_inset

 is unique; the other 
\begin_inset Formula $n-1$
\end_inset

 roots are complex; they are arranged in a roughly evenly-spaced ring on
 the complex plane, not far from the unit circle, reminiscent of roots of
 unity.
 There is always a positive real root, which satisfies 
\begin_inset Formula $1\le r_{n}<2$
\end_inset

; the real roots and the polynomials are in one-to-one correspondence.
 The roots must be bracketed (to the left and right) by the roots of polynomials
 occurring earlier in the sequence; if the root is not bracketed, then the
 corresponding polynomial does not appear in the list.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The bracketing constraint can be represented by a recursive function 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{n}\left(\rho\right)$
\end_inset

 returning a boolean true/false value, as to whether a given polynomial
 is acceptable.
 It is
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\theta_{n}\left(\rho\right)=\begin{cases}
\Theta\left(r_{n/2}-\rho\right)\cdot\theta_{n/2}\left(\rho\right) & \mbox{ for \ensuremath{n} even }\\
\theta_{\left\lfloor n/2\right\rfloor }\left(\rho\right) & \mbox{ for \ensuremath{n} odd }
\end{cases}\label{eq:theta mask}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

This uses a definition for the Heaviside 
\begin_inset Formula $\Theta\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 that is one only for strictly positive 
\begin_inset Formula $x>0$
\end_inset

, and is zero otherwise.
 In numerical work, the test should be bounded away from zero.
 The recursion compares the candidate 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 to some root at each lower order.
 The recursion terminates at 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{0}\left(\rho\right)=1$
\end_inset

.
 The index 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 corresponds to a valid polynomial, and thus a valid root, if and only if
 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{n}\left(r_{n}\right)=1$
\end_inset

.
 Effectively, this states that roots of higher-order polynomials must be
 less than a certain sequence of lower-order roots.
 This is visible in the location of the discontinuities in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Location-of-Midpoints"

\end_inset

: new discontinuities at higher orders must occur to the left of earlier
 ones.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For example, the polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta^{3}-\beta-1$
\end_inset

 is excluded from the list simply because it is not an iterate of an earlier
 polynomial, even though it has the interesting real root 
\begin_inset Formula $1.324717957244746\cdots$
\end_inset

, the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

silver constant
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 The numbering scheme does not even have a way of numbering this particular
 polynomial.
 Despite this, the silver constant does appear, but a bit later, as the
 root of 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{8}=\beta^{5}-\beta^{4}-1$
\end_inset

, which is an allowed polynomial.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{5}=\beta^{4}-\beta^{3}-\beta-1$
\end_inset

 is excluded because it has 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi=1.618\cdots$
\end_inset

 as a root, which was previously observed by 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 The polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{9}=\beta^{5}-\beta^{4}-\beta-1$
\end_inset

 is excluded because it's root, 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{9}=1.497094048762796\cdots$
\end_inset

 is greater than its predecessor 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{2}$
\end_inset

; the recursive algorithm does not compare it to 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{4}$
\end_inset

.
 Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{9}$
\end_inset

 is relatively prime to the earlier polynomials, so irreducibility is not
 a sufficient criterion; the root must also be less.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The indexing has the property that, whenever 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{n}\left(r_{n}\right)=1$
\end_inset

, the integer 
\begin_inset Formula $2n+1$
\end_inset

, expressed as a binary bitstring, encodes both the coefficients of the
 polynomial, and also the orbit of the midpoint.
 This can be taken as an alternate, non-recursive definition of 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{n}$
\end_inset

: it is one if and only if the orbit of 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{n}$
\end_inset

 encodes the bitsequence of 2n+1.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The degree 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

 of the polynomial is identical to the length 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

 of the orbit; it is 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu=\left\lceil \log_{2}\left(2n+1\right)\right\rceil $
\end_inset

.
 The bits 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{i}$
\end_inset

 of the bitstring 
\begin_inset Formula $2n+1=b_{0}b_{1}b_{2}\cdots b_{\nu}$
\end_inset

 correspond to the orbit as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
b_{i}=\Theta\left(T_{\beta}^{i}\left(\frac{\beta}{2}\right)-\frac{1}{2}\right)=d_{i}\left(\frac{1}{2}\right)=k_{i}\left(\frac{\beta}{2}\right)
\]

\end_inset

where the 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{i}$
\end_inset

 are as given before, in eqn 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:rescaled-bitseq"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, and the 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{i}$
\end_inset

 as in eqn 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:down-bits"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{0}=1$
\end_inset

 always corresponds to 
\begin_inset Formula $1/2<\beta/2$
\end_inset

, always.
 By convention, the last digit is always 1, also.
