\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{m}=\psi\left(m\right)$
\end_inset

.
 It is convenient to start the sequence at 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{0}=0$
\end_inset

.
 This corresponds to 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta=2$
\end_inset

; at the far left, for 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta=1$
\end_inset

, write 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{-1}=\infty$
\end_inset

.
 The function 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{m}$
\end_inset

 encodes the locations of one-bits in the bitmask 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

, and so 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta\left(\psi_{m}\right)=1$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The summatory function of the indicator is 
\begin_inset Formula $S\left(k\right)=\sum_{n=1}^{k}\theta_{n}$
\end_inset

.
 It counts the total number of one-bits below the location 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

.
 The validity sequence is the pullback of the summatory function.
 Each 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{m}$
\end_inset

 is the smallest integer 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 for which 
\begin_inset Formula $m=S\left(k\right)$
\end_inset

 holds true, and so one has 
\begin_inset Formula $m=S\left(\psi_{m}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 The pullback can be expressed as 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi\left(m\right)=\psi\left(S\left(\psi\left(m\right)\right)\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A few additional properties may be noted:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
For all 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta\left(2^{m}\right)=\theta\left(2^{m}-1\right)=1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta\left(m\right)=1$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta\left(2m\right)=1$
\end_inset

.
 By recursion, 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta\left(2^{n}m\right)=1$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 is odd, and if 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta\left(m\right)=1$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta\left(\left(m-1\right)/2\right)=1$
\end_inset

.
 This is reminiscent of the Collatz conjecture.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta\left(m\right)=0$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta\left(2^{n}\left(2m+1\right)\right)=0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

