\begin_layout Standard
It is convenient to partition 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi$
\end_inset

 into ranks 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

 that correspond to the length of the orbits, or equivalently, the order
 of the defining polynomial.
 Examining the earlier tables, the rank of 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu\left(n\right)=\left\lfloor \log_{2}n\right\rfloor +2$
\end_inset

.
 The partition is then 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi=\bigcup_{\nu=1}^{\infty}\Psi_{\nu}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi_{\nu}=\left\{ n\in\Psi:\nu\left(n\right)=\nu\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 As before, it is convenient to extend the partition so that it can deal
 with the endpoints 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta=1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta=2$
\end_inset

; this is a kind of (two-point) compactification of these and other various
 sequences and sets.
 The compactification here is to write 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu\left(0\right)=1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu\left(-1\right)=\infty$
\end_inset

, which allows components 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi_{1}=\left\{ 0\right\} $
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi_{\infty}=\left\{ -1\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 The size of each component is 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\Psi_{\nu}\right|=M_{\nu}$
\end_inset

 given by Moreau's necklace counting function 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{\nu}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The representation of 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

