\begin_layout Subsubsection
Leaders
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An important subsequence consists of the leaders of the doubling sequences.
 These can be defined in several equivalent ways.
 One property of the bitmask is that if 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta\left(m\right)=1$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta\left(2^{n}m\right)=1$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
 A leader 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 is the smallest such 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 at the front of such a doubling sequence: it is either an odd number 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=\left(2k+1\right)$
\end_inset

 satisfying 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta\left(\lambda\right)=1$
\end_inset

 or it is an even number of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=2^{h}\left(2k+1\right),h>0$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta\left(2^{h}\left(2k+1\right)\right)=1$
\end_inset

 but 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta\left(2^{h-1}\left(2k+1\right)\right)=0$
\end_inset

.
 The minimal power 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 defining the leader will be called the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

height of the leader
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Equivalently, the leaders can be defined as a subsequence of 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{m}$
\end_inset

.
 By definition, one has that 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta\left(\psi_{m}\right)=1$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{m}$
\end_inset

 is odd, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{m}$
\end_inset

 is a leader.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{m}$
\end_inset

 is even, then it is a leader if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta\left(\psi_{m}/2\right)=0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Given a valid index 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{m}$
\end_inset

, it is useful to define a function 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda$
\end_inset

 that provides the map 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Lambda\left(\psi_{m}\right)=2^{h}\left(2\psi_{m}+1\right)\label{eq:Leadership function}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

This map is not monotonic: 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda\left(1\right)=3$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda\left(2\right)=10$
\end_inset

 but 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda\left(3\right)=7$
\end_inset

.
 It is, however, one-to-one, as leaders are always a product of an odd number
 times some power of two.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Sorting the leaders into ascending order, the start of the sequence is 1,3,7,10,
13,15,25,29,31,...
 This sequence is not currently known to OEIS.
 It is handy to count from one, and to assign 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{0}=0$
\end_inset

, so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{1}=1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{2}=3$
\end_inset

 and so on.
\end_layout

