\begin_layout Subsubsection
Bracketing intervals
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
That this figure is a self-similar fractal is presumably self-evident.
 Thus, for example, the graph to to right of 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{1}=\varphi=1.618...$
\end_inset

 repeats again between 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{1}$
\end_inset

 and again between 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{4}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Each such bracketed interval contains a unique largest discontinuity; it
 can be seen as being at the front of a doubling sequence.
 Each discontinuity is in one-to-one correspondence with a bracketing interval;
 the bracketing intervals are all self-similar to one-another.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A distinct notation for bracketed intervals is useful.
 Write 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell\Mapsto f\Mapsfrom\rho$
\end_inset

 for the discontinuity 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 bracketed on the left and right by 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

.
 By 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

left
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

right
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, it is literally meant that the three roots are in order, with 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{\ell}<r_{f}<r_{\rho}$
\end_inset

 with the inequalities being strict.
 Not all ascending sequences of three roots form a valid bracket; valid
 brackets are obtained by recursive subdivision; this is given in the next
 section.
 But first, some examples.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Taking the liberty to write 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{0}=2$
\end_inset

, the interval to the right of 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{1}$
\end_inset

 is then 
\begin_inset Formula $1\Mapsto3\Mapsfrom0$
\end_inset

.
 The most prominent self-similar intervals are then 
\begin_inset Formula $2\Mapsto10\Mapsfrom1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $4\Mapsto36\Mapsfrom2$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $8\Mapsto136\Mapsfrom4$
\end_inset

.
 In each of these examples, the front was also a leader, with leadership
 as defined in the previous section.
 This is not always the case: the brackets 
\begin_inset Formula $1\Mapsto6\Mapsfrom3$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $1\Mapsto12\Mapsfrom6$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $1\Mapsto24\Mapsfrom12$
\end_inset

 are clearly visible; they are a part of an index-doubling sequence.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The extreme left side can be assigned the index of 
\begin_inset Formula $\infty$
\end_inset

 so that 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{\infty}=1$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, the entire interval 
\begin_inset Formula $1\le\beta\le2$
\end_inset

 corresponds to the bracket 
\begin_inset Formula $\infty\Mapsto1\Mapsfrom0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
The bracket tree
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The brackets can be arranged into a binary tree, recursively defined.
 Any valid interval 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell\Mapsto f\Mapsfrom\rho$
\end_inset

 can be split into two: the left side and the right side.
 These two pieces are 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell\Mapsto2f\Mapsfrom f$
\end_inset

 on the left, and 
\begin_inset Formula $f\Mapsto\Lambda\left(f\right)\Mapsfrom\rho$
\end_inset

 on the right, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda$
\end_inset

 is the leader function given by eqn 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Leadership function"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 in the previous section.
 Recursion starts with 
\begin_inset Formula $\infty\Mapsto1\Mapsfrom0$
\end_inset

.
 A bracketing relationship is valid if and only if it appears in this recursive
 binary tree.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The left and right moves 
\begin_inset Formula $L,\mathfrak{R}$
\end_inset

 on the binary tree can then be written as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
L & :\left(\ell\Mapsto f\Mapsfrom\rho\right)\mapsto\left(\ell\Mapsto2f\Mapsfrom f\right)\label{eq:Bracket recursion}\\
\mathfrak{R} & :\left(\ell\Mapsto f\Mapsfrom\rho\right)\mapsto\left(f\Mapsto\Lambda\left(f\right)\Mapsfrom\rho\right)\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset

The right-move is denoted with a fraktur 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{R}$
\end_inset

 instead of a roman 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 in order to distinguish between the action of the leader function, and
 the conventional dyadic map 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
L & :m\mapsto2m\\
R & :m\mapsto2m+1
\end{align*}

\end_inset

The issue is that not all dyadic 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 moves result in a valid index: having 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta\left(m\right)=1$
\end_inset

 does not generally imply that 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta\left(2m+1\right)$
\end_inset

 is one.
 However, the leader function does provide a successor that is always valid:
 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta\left(\Lambda\left(m\right)\right)=1$
\end_inset

 is guaranteed by construction.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Any sequence of 
\begin_inset Formula $L,\mathfrak{R}$
\end_inset

 moves is guaranteed to produce a valid interval; every location in the
 binary tree is mapped to a valid index by the bracket recursion moves.
 A general location on the bracket tree is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
G=L^{a_{1}}\mathfrak{R}^{a_{2}}L^{a_{3}}\cdots\mathfrak{R}^{a_{k}}
\]

\end_inset

and this has the property that if 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta\left(m\right)=1$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta\left(G\left(m\right)\right)=1$
\end_inset

.
 Equivalently, if 
\begin_inset Formula $m\in\Psi$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $G\left(m\right)\in\Psi$
\end_inset

.
 This implies that the bracket recursion relations generate all of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi$
\end_inset

.
 Starting at 
\begin_inset Formula $m=1$
\end_inset

, all left-right moves produce elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi$
\end_inset

; conversely, every element of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi$
\end_inset

 can be expressed as some sequence of left-right moves applied to 
\begin_inset Formula $m=1$
\end_inset

.
 It is convenient to take 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 as the function that produces only the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

good
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 indexes.
 Thus
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
G:L^{a_{1}}R^{a_{2}}L^{a_{3}}\cdots R^{a_{k}}\mapsto L^{a_{1}}\mathfrak{R}^{a_{2}}L^{a_{3}}\cdots\mathfrak{R}^{a_{k}}
\]

\end_inset

Labeling the nodes of the binary tree with the natural numbers 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

 provides a bijection 
\begin_inset Formula $G:\mathbb{N}\to\Psi$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The bracket recursion relations split the interval 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{\ell}<r_{f}<r_{\rho}$
\end_inset

 into left and right pieces, as well.
 That is, each node of the binary tree is labeled by some (unique) 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{f}$
\end_inset

, with the root 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{\ell}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{\rho}$
