\begin_layout Subsubsection
The finite comb
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Theta-Indicator"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 shows each indicator rank 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi_{\nu}$
\end_inset

 as a comb.
 A better understanding is gained by mapping this to the infinite binary
 tree.
 Each rank 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

 corresponds to a single horizontal row in the tree.
 The numbering that has been adopted is that 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu=2$
\end_inset

 is at the root of the tree.
 The dyadic left and right moves on the comb are
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
L & :\theta_{m}\mapsto\theta_{2m}\\
R & :\theta_{m}\mapsto\theta_{2m+1}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

The indicator function marks each node in the tree with a zero or a one.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One property of this marking is that when a node is marked with a zero,
 all nodes in the right subtree are marked with a zero, as well: the presence
 of a zero removes the entire right-hand branch under that point.
 This follows from the property noted earlier, that if 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta\left(m\right)=0$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta\left(2^{n}\left(2m+1\right)\right)=0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
 Restating in terms of moves, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{m}=0$
\end_inset

 then, taking 
\begin_inset Formula $n=0$
\end_inset

, one has 
\begin_inset Formula $R\theta_{m}=\theta_{2m+1}=0$
\end_inset

.
 Of course it, follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $RR\theta_{m}=0$
\end_inset

.
 Taking 
\begin_inset Formula $n=1$
\end_inset

, one has that 
\begin_inset Formula $LR\theta_{m}=0$
\end_inset

, and so both left and right sub-branches are gone.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A converse marking is given by the property that, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta\left(m\right)=1$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta\left(2m\right)=1$
\end_inset

.
 On the tree, this means that left-branches of a node marked with a one
 are never trimmed: if 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{m}=1$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $L\theta_{m}=1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Write 
\begin_inset Formula $2^{<\omega}$
\end_inset

 for the collection of all finite strings in the letters 
\begin_inset Formula $L,R$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $2^{\omega}$
\end_inset

 as the set of all infinite strings.
 The indicator function is then a map 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta:2^{<\omega}\to\left\{ 0,1\right\} $
\end_inset

 that indicates when a given finite, unbounded walk down the tree might
 have more branches, or definitely does not.
 This definitely-maybe marking defines a filter, and dually, an ideal.
 The filter/ideal can be taken on the integers, or equivalently, on the
 reals.
 The second possibility is what the figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Theta-Indicator"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 is hinting at.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The filter has the form that if 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\Psi_{\nu}$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $2n\in\Psi_{v+1}$
\end_inset

.
 The converse is not true: 
\begin_inset Formula $10\in\Psi_{5}$
\end_inset

 but 
\begin_inset Formula $5\notin\Psi_{4}$
\end_inset

.
 Written as a filter, this is 
\begin_inset Formula $L\Psi_{\nu}\subset\Psi_{\nu+1}$
\end_inset

 and the subset relation is strict.
 Written as and ideal, if 
\begin_inset Formula $n\notin\Psi_{\nu}$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(2n+1\right)\notin\Psi_{v+1}$
\end_inset

.
 This is more clearly stated with set complements at a given rank.
 Define the unit interval 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{\nu}=\left\{ n:2^{\nu-2}\le n<2^{\nu-1}\right\} $
\end_inset

 and the set complement 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\Psi}_{\nu}=I_{\nu}\backslash\Psi_{\nu}$
\end_inset

.
 The ideal is then 
\begin_inset Formula $R\overline{\Psi}_{\nu}\subset\overline{\Psi}_{\nu+1}$
\end_inset

 together with 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(LR\overline{\Psi}_{\nu}\cup RR\overline{\Psi}_{\nu}\right)\subset\overline{\Psi}_{\nu+2}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
The comb bijection
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The good-index bijection 
\begin_inset Formula $G:\mathbb{N}\to\Psi$
\end_inset

 provides a mechanism to map the full binary tree into the trimmed tree,
 so that every node in the trimmed tree is in one-to-one correspondence
 with the full binary tree.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The leadership function provides the desired mapping.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\Psi_{\nu}$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda\left(n\right)\in\Psi_{\nu+1+h}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 was the height of the leader.
 Any valid index 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 gets 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

kicked upstairs
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 by the leadership function; one can write 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda\Psi_{\nu}\subset\bigcup_{h=0}^{\infty}\Psi_{\nu+1+h}$
\end_inset

.
 This just corresponds to the bracket move 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{R}:\theta_{m}\to\theta_{\Lambda\left(m\right)}$
\end_inset

 on the trimmed tree: given any location 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta\left(m\right)=1$
\end_inset

 in the trimmed tree, the bracket right move returns the next valid right
 branch in the trimmed tree: 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{R}\left(m\right)=\Lambda\left(m\right)$
\end_inset

, since, by construction, 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta\left(\Lambda\left(m\right)\right)=1$
\end_inset

 whenever 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta\left(m\right)=1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
The infinite comb
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The comb is mapped to the reals by defining open subsets bounded by the
 dyadic rationals.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
I\left(m,\nu\right)=\left\{ x\in\mathbb{R}:m<x2^{\nu-2}<\left(m+1\right);0\le m<2^{\nu-2}\right\} \label{eq:topo-base}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

so that 
\begin_inset Formula $I\left(0,2\right)=\left\{ x\in\mathbb{R}:0<x<1\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 The left and right moves are the obvious ones: 
\begin_inset Formula $LI\left(m,\nu\right)=I\left(2m,\nu+1\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $RI\left(m,\nu\right)=I\left(2m+1,\nu+1\right)$
\end_inset

.
 These are interpreted as the left and right halves of the (fat) Cantor
 set, on the reals; the fat Cantor set being taken as the reals with the
 dyadic rationals removed.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The filters on 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi_{\nu}$
\end_inset

 become filters on 
\begin_inset Formula $I\left(m,\nu\right)$
\end_inset

 in the obvious way, by means of a commuting diagram.
 Write 
\begin_inset Formula $I\left(\Psi_{\nu}\right)=\bigcup_{m\in\Psi_{\nu}}I\left(m-2^{\nu-2},\nu\right)$
\end_inset

 as the union of intervals that cover the nonempty runs in the binary tree.
 This is effectively what is being graphed in the figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Theta-Indicator"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 The limit set is then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\overline{\theta}=\bigcap_{\nu=2}^{\infty}I\left(\Psi_{\nu}\right)\label{eq:infinite comb}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where the notation 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\theta}$
\end_inset

 is happily abused to denote the limit of the indicator function 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{n}$
\end_inset

 as a subset of the reals.
 This is possible precisely because 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{n}$
\end_inset

 can be mapped to the binary tree, which can then be partitioned as filters
 and ideals.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since 
\begin_inset Formula $2^{\nu-2}\in\Psi_{\nu}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 the leftmost branch is never trimmed, one easily concludes that 
\begin_inset Formula $0\in\overline{\theta}$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(2^{\nu-1}-1\right)\in\Psi_{\nu}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

, the rightmost branch is never trimmed, and so one may conclude that 
\begin_inset Formula $1\in\overline{\theta}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It should be clear that the set 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\theta}$
\end_inset

 is isomorphic to the Cantor set.
 The comb bijection show how to map points in 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\theta}$
\end_inset

 back into the untrimmed infinite tree; the full binary tree is isomorphic
 to the Cantor set.
 From this, one concludes that the set 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\theta}$
\end_inset

 is uncountable, and can be placed in bijection with the reals.
 This is explored in the next section.
 A measure can be assigned to 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\theta}$
\end_inset

.
 This is given in the section after next.
 A slightly more formal examination of 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\theta}$
\end_inset

 will be given in a later section on eventually-periodic orbits.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Self-describing orbits
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
What is the meaning of the finite and infinite combs? The finite comb is
 a mapping of of the valid-index set 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi$
\end_inset

 to the dyadics.
 The infinite comb is the clusre of the finite comb in the reals.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A polynomial index 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\Psi$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 encodes a self-describing finite orbit.
 That is, 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\Psi$
\end_inset

 if and only if the real root 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{n}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{n}\left(r_{n}\right)=0$
\end_inset

 iterates under the 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

-map such that the iterate reproduces the bit-sequence of 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
 That is, 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\Psi$
\end_inset

 if and only if the bits 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{i}$
\end_inset

 of the bitstring 
\begin_inset Formula $2n+1=b_{0}b_{1}b_{2}\cdots b_{\nu}$
\end_inset

 are given by the (finite) orbit as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
b_{i}=\Theta\left(T_{\beta}^{i}\left(\frac{r_{n}}{2}\right)-\frac{1}{2}\right)=k_{i}\left(\frac{r_{n}}{2}\right)
\]

\end_inset

If 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 does not have this property, then 
\begin_inset Formula $n\notin\Psi$
\end_inset

.
 At each rank 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

, the elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi_{v}$
\end_inset

 correspond to finite orbits of length 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

.
 In the limit of 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu\to\infty$
\end_inset

, one gets self-describing orbits of unbounded (infinite) length.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By construction, if 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\Psi_{\nu}$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $Ln\in\Psi_{\nu+1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda n\in\Psi_{\nu+1+h}$
\end_inset

.
 That is, if 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is a self-describing orbit, then it appears as the prefix of longer self-descri
bing orbits.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Polynomials of infinite order are holomorphic functions.
 Given an infinite bitsequence 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ b\right\} =b_{0}b_{1}\cdots$
\end_inset

, define a holomorphic function
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
q^{\left\{ b\right\} }\left(\zeta\right)=1-\sum_{j=0}^{\infty}b_{j}\zeta^{j+1}
\]

\end_inset

If the bit-sequence is finite, in that all 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{j}=0$
\end_inset

 when 
\begin_inset Formula $j>k$
\end_inset

, then this is related to the polynomials as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\zeta^{k+1}p_{n}\left(\frac{1}{\zeta}\right)=1-b_{0}\zeta-b_{1}\zeta^{2}-\cdots-b_{k}\zeta^{k+1}
\]

\end_inset

Given any arbitrary sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ b\right\} $
\end_inset

, the holomorphic function 
\begin_inset Formula $q^{\left\{ b\right\} }\left(\zeta\right)$
\end_inset

 will have a single, unique real, positive root.
 To make contact with the polynomials, write this as the reciprocal, so
 that the root 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 satisfies 
\begin_inset Formula $q^{\left\{ b\right\} }\left(1/r\right)=0$
\end_inset

.
 This root will have some orbit, given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a_{i}=\Theta\left(T_{\beta}^{i}\left(\frac{r}{2}\right)-\frac{1}{2}\right)=k_{i}\left(\frac{r}{2}\right)
\]

\end_inset

Such an orbit is self-describing if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ a\right\} =\left\{ b\right\} $
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The claim being pursued here is that the infinite comb contains all self-describ
ing sequences, and conversely, every element of the comb corresponds to
 a self-describing bit-sequence.
 That is, if
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x=\sum_{j=0}^{\infty}\frac{b_{j}}{2^{j}}\in\overline{\theta}
\]

\end_inset

then
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x=2\left(1-q^{\left\{ b\right\} }\left(\frac{1}{2}\right)\right)
\]

\end_inset

Every real number 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\overline{\theta}$
\end_inset

 in the comb corresponds to such a self-describing orbit.
 A proof of these claims will be given in a later section, after the development
 of some formal definitions.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the meanwhile, it can be noted that every rational number corresponds
 to a bitsequence that is ultimately periodic.
 After an initial unstable finite sequence, the bitstring settles down to
 a cyclic orbit.
 One task ahead is to examine the set 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}\cap\overline{\theta}$
\end_inset

: this is the set of self-describing eventually-periodic infinite-length
 orbits.
 It turns out these can be readily described as root of a finite polynomial.
 The holomorphic function 
\begin_inset Formula $q^{\left\{ b\right\} }\left(\zeta\right)$
\end_inset

 to be factored into two finite polynomials, one describing the initial
 aperiodic segment, and a second describing the cyclic segment.
 Such orbits are examined in a later section.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Formal definitions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A sufficient number of distinct concepts have been introduced, that some
 basic housekeeping is in order.
 The definitions that follow are straight-forward and conventional.
 The goal is to provide a workable vocabulary for further discussion.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{B}$
\end_inset

 denote the finite but unbounded binary tree, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\mathbb{B}}$
\end_inset

 it's closure as the infinite tree.
 The infinite tree is, of course, isomorphic to the Cantor space 
\begin_inset Formula $2^{\omega}$
\end_inset

; but this mechanism is not currently needed.
 A more careful definition of the finite tree is needed.
 Thus, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{B}$
\end_inset

 the the graph of vertices and connecting edges 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{B}=\left\{ v_{i},e_{ij}:i\in\mathbb{N},j\in\left\{ 2i,2i+1\right\} \right\} $
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta:\mathbb{N}\to\mathbb{B}$
\end_inset

 denote the canonical labeling of the binary tree by the positive integers,
 so that the root of the tree is given the label 1, the first row is 2,3
 and the next row is 4,5,6,7.
 This is a bijection: every finite walk down the tree can be labeled with
 a positive integer.
 The walks are left and right moves, in the canonical sense: 
\begin_inset Formula $L:\mathbb{N}\to\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $L:m\mapsto2m$
\end_inset

 and likewise 
\begin_inset Formula $R:\mathbb{N}\to\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $R:m\mapsto2m+1$
\end_inset

.
 The pushforward of 
\begin_inset Formula $L,R$
\end_inset

 provide the canonical walks on the tree, as a commuting diagram, so that
 
\begin_inset Formula $L\circ\eta=\eta\circ L$
\end_inset

 and likewise 
\begin_inset Formula $R\circ\eta=\eta\circ R$
\end_inset

.
 It is useful to adjoin the pre-root elements 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ 0,\infty\right\} $
\end_inset

 so that 
\begin_inset Formula $R:0\to1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $L:\infty\to1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{D}$
\end_inset

 be the dyadic rationals, with the canonical bijection to the natural numbers
 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta:\mathbb{D}\to\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

 given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta:\left(2n+1\right)/2^{m}\mapsto2^{m-1}+n$
\end_inset

.
 This labels the root of the tree with 1/2, and the first row under it as
 1/4 and 3/4.
 The left and right moves are 
\begin_inset Formula $L:\left(2n+1\right)/2^{m}\mapsto\left(4n+1\right)/2^{m+1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $R:\left(2n+1\right)/2^{m}\mapsto\left(4n+3\right)/2^{m+1}$
\end_inset

.
 This was set up so that 
\begin_inset Formula $L\circ\delta=\delta\circ L$
\end_inset

 and likewise 
\begin_inset Formula $R\circ\delta=\delta\circ R$
\end_inset

.
 The map 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta^{-1}:\mathbb{N}\to\mathbb{D}$
\end_inset

 is equally familiar: it is 
\begin_inset Formula $n=b_{0}b_{1}\cdots b_{k}\mapsto\sum_{n=0}^{k}b_{n}2^{-n-1}$
\end_inset

 that interprets 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

 as a sequence of 
\begin_inset Formula $L,R$
\end_inset

 moves in the binrary tree, returning the fraction found at that location.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This allows the bracket tree and the good-index bijection to be specified
 more precisely.
 The validity set 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi\subset\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

 is defined in eqn 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:valid index set"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 as the collection of natural number indexes corresponding to polynomials
 with self-describing roots.
 This set came with two functions 
\begin_inset Formula $L,\mathfrak{R}:\Psi\to\Psi$
\end_inset

 given by index-doubling 
\begin_inset Formula $L:m\mapsto2m$
\end_inset

 and leadership (eqn
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Leadership function"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{R}:m\mapsto\Lambda\left(m\right)$
\end_inset

.
 The good-index bijection 
\begin_inset Formula $G:\mathbb{N}\to\Psi$
\end_inset

 is then defined as the pullback 
\begin_inset Formula $L\circ G=G\circ L$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{R}\circ G=G\circ R$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The trimmed tree 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{B}\subset\mathbb{B}$
\end_inset

 is the image of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi$
\end_inset

 under the mapping 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta$
\end_inset

, so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{B}=\eta\Psi$
\end_inset

.
 This consists of those nodes and edges in the finite binary tree that are
 labeled by integers from the validity set 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi$
\end_inset

.
 The good-index function 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 places the trimmed tree and the finite tree in a bijection, so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{B}=\eta G\eta^{-1}\mathbb{B}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The root map 
\begin_inset Formula $r:\Psi\to\left[1,2\right]$
\end_inset

 takes valid integer indexes, and maps them to the roots of the corresponding
 (finite-orbit) polynomials, so that 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{n}\left(r_{n}\right)=0$
