\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
S_{\nu}\left(k\right)=S\left(k\right)-S\left(2^{\nu-2}-1\right)
\]

\end_inset

The intent is to isolate the range 
\begin_inset Formula $2^{\nu-2}\le k<2^{\nu-1}$
\end_inset

, and to split the sum 
\begin_inset Formula $S\left(k\right)$
\end_inset

 into a collection of ranks 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{\nu}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
At the end of the range, the sum 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{\nu}$
\end_inset

 achieves Moreau's necklace-counting function: 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{\nu}\left(2^{\nu-1}-1\right)=M_{\nu}$
\end_inset

.
 Dividing by 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{\nu}$
\end_inset

 gives each rank the same vertical scale: zero to one.
 It is also useful to rescale the horizontal range, to run zero-to-one as
 well.
 This gives a normalized version
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
F_{\nu}\left(x\right)=\frac{S_{\nu}\left(\left\lfloor 2^{\nu-2}\left(1+x\right)\right\rfloor \right)}{M_{\nu}}
\]

\end_inset

that runs from zero to one as 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 runs from zero to one.
 This function does not have an interesting limit as 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu\to\infty$
\end_inset

, as it slowly drops to zero over the entire unit interval.
 However, it does so at a fixed rate, and can be held constant with a radical.
 The sequence of functions
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
A_{\nu}\left(x\right)=\exp\left(M_{\nu}2^{-\nu}\log F_{\nu}\left(x\right)\right)\label{eq:indicator-sum}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

converge rapidly and more-or-less uniformly to a limit 
\begin_inset Formula $A\left(x\right)=\lim_{\nu\to\infty}A_{\nu}\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

.
 It appears to be well-defined on the unit real interval 
\begin_inset Formula $0\le x\le1$
\end_inset

.
 This is the limit shown in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Indicator-Sum"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

