\begin_layout Standard
All of these integer sequences and roots participate in a number of curious
 relations having a regular form; this is, of course, the whole point of
 listing them in the OEIS.
 This suggests a question: do the known relationships generalize to the
 beta-shift setting?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For example, the polynomials of the form 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\beta^{k+1}-\beta-1=0
\]

\end_inset

are the Lamé polynomials, they arise as solutions to Lamé's equation, a
 kind of ellipsoidal harmonic differential equation.
 In the present notation, these correspond to polynomials 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{n}\left(\beta\right)=0$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $n=2^{k}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Another example is the Fibonacci-tribonacci-tetranacci sequence of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

generalized golden means
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 These are the roots of the series for which all 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{k}=1$
\end_inset

, that is, the roots of 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\beta^{k+1}-\beta^{k}-\beta^{k-1}-\cdots-1=0
\]

\end_inset

In the present notation, these would be the polynomials 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{n}\left(\beta\right)=0$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $n=2^{k}-1$
\end_inset

.
 Such roots can be rapidly computed by a series provided by Hare, Prodinger
 and Shallit
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Hare14"
literal "true"

\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{1}{\alpha_{k}}=\frac{1}{2}+\frac{1}{2}\sum_{j=1}^{\infty}\frac{1}{j}{j\left(k+1\right) \choose j-1}\frac{1}{2^{j\left(k+1\right)}}
\]

\end_inset

This series is obtained by making good use of the Lagrange inversion formula.
 Here, 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{k}$
\end_inset

 is the 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

'th generalized golden mean, i.e.
 the solution 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{2^{k}-1}\left(\alpha_{k}\right)=0$
\end_inset

.
 Can the Hare series be extended to provide the roots 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{n}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{n}\left(r_{n}\right)=0$
\end_inset

 for general 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Another set of observations seem to invoke the theory of complex multiplication
 on elliptic curves, and pose additional questions.
 So:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The tribonacci root 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{3}$
\end_inset

 is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
r_{3}=\frac{1}{3}\left(1+\sqrt[3]{19+3\sqrt{33}}+\sqrt[3]{19-3\sqrt{33}}\right)\simeq1.839\cdots
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The silver number (plastic number) 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{8}$
\end_inset

 is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
r_{8}=\frac{1}{6}\left(\sqrt[3]{108+12\sqrt{69}}+\sqrt[3]{108-12\sqrt{69}}\right)\simeq1.324\cdots
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Narayana's cows number 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{2}$
\end_inset

 is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
r_{2}=\frac{1}{6}\sqrt[3]{116+12\sqrt{93}}+\frac{2}{3\sqrt[3]{116+12\sqrt{93}}}+\frac{1}{3}\simeq1.645\cdots
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The root 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{6}$
\end_inset

 is related to the silver number 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{8}$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{8}=r_{6}\left(r_{6}-1\right)$
\end_inset

 and is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
r_{6}=\frac{1}{6}\sqrt[3]{108+12\sqrt{69}}+\frac{2}{\left(\sqrt[3]{108+12\sqrt{69}}\right)^{2}}\simeq1.754\cdots
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Do the other roots have comparable expressions? To obtain them, is it sufficient
 to articulate the theory of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

complex multiplication
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 on elliptic curves? Are these just disguised solutions to Lamé's ellipsoidal
 harmonic differential equation? The appearance of only the cube and square
 roots is certainly suggestive of an underlying process of points on elliptic
 curves.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

-Fibonacci sequences as shifts
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The nature of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

-Fibonacci sequences as shift sequences can be emphasized by noting that
 they arise from the iteration of the 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "companion matrix"
target "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Companion_matrix"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 for the polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{n}\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

.
 This is a 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(k+1\right)\times\left(k+1\right)$
\end_inset

 matrix in 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "lower-Hessenberg form"
target "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hessenberg_matrix"
literal "false"

\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
B=\left[\begin{array}{cccccc}
b_{0} & 1 & 0 & 0 & \cdots & 0\\
b_{1} & 0 & 1 & 0 & \cdots & 0\\
b_{2} & 0 & 0 & 1 & \cdots & 0\\
\vdots & \vdots & \vdots &  & \ddots & \vdots\\
b_{k-1} & 0 & 0 & 0 & \cdots & 1\\
b_{k} & 0 & 0 & 0 & \cdots & 0
\end{array}\right]\label{eq:golden matrix}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Iteration produces a 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "linear recursive sequence"
target "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear_recursive_sequence"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 this is the 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

-Fibonacci sequence.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

'th element of the sequence is obtained from the 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

'th iterate 
\begin_inset Formula $B^{m}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Define the 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "exchange matrix"
target "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Exchange_matrix"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
J=\left[\begin{array}{ccccc}
0 & 0 & \cdots & 0 & 1\\
0 & 0 & \cdots & 1 & 0\\
\vdots & \vdots & \iddots &  & \vdots\\
0 & 1 & \cdots & 0 & 0\\
1 & 0 & \cdots & 0 & 0
\end{array}\right]
\]

\end_inset

This can be used to write the above in the more conventional companion-matrix
 form:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
C=\left[JBJ\right]^{\mathrm{T}}=\left[\begin{array}{cccccc}
0 & 1 & 0 & 0 & \cdots & 0\\
0 & 0 & 1 & 0 & \cdots & 0\\
0 & 0 & 0 & 1 & \cdots & 0\\
\vdots & \vdots & \vdots &  & \ddots & \vdots\\
0 & 0 & 0 & 0 & \cdots & 1\\
b_{k} & b_{k-1} & b_{k-2} & b_{k-3} & \cdots & b_{0}
\end{array}\right]
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Some explicit examples are in order.
 For the golden ratio, one has 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
B=\left[\begin{array}{cc}
1 & 1\\
1 & 0
\end{array}\right]
\]

\end_inset

and the iterates are 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
B^{2}=\left[\begin{array}{cc}
2 & 1\\
1 & 1
\end{array}\right],\;B^{3}=\left[\begin{array}{cc}
3 & 2\\
2 & 1
\end{array}\right],\;B^{4}=\left[\begin{array}{cc}
5 & 3\\
3 & 2
\end{array}\right],\;B^{n}=\left[\begin{array}{cc}
F_{n} & F_{n-1}\\
F_{n-1} & F_{n-2}
\end{array}\right]
\]

\end_inset

with 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{n}$
\end_inset

 being the 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

'th Fibonacci number, as usual.
 For the general case, after 
\begin_inset Formula $m\ge k-1$
\end_inset

 iterations, one gets the 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "Hankel matrix"
target "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hankel_matrix"
literal "false"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
B^{m}=\left[\begin{array}{cccccc}
F_{m}^{\left\{ b\right\} } & F_{m-1}^{\left\{ b\right\} } & F_{m-2}^{\left\{ b\right\} } & \cdots & F_{m-k+1}^{\left\{ b\right\} } & F_{m-k}^{\left\{ b\right\} }\\
F_{m-1}^{\left\{ b\right\} } & F_{m-2}^{\left\{ b\right\} } & F_{m-3}^{\left\{ b\right\} } & \cdots & F_{m-k}^{\left\{ b\right\} } & F_{m-k-1}^{\left\{ b\right\} }\\
F_{m-2}^{\left\{ b\right\} } & F_{m-3}^{\left\{ b\right\} } &  & \cdots\\
\vdots & \vdots & \vdots & \ddots & \vdots & \vdots\\
F_{m-k+1}^{\left\{ b\right\} } &  &  & \cdots\\
F_{m-k}^{\left\{ b\right\} } &  &  & \cdots &  & F_{m-2k}^{\left\{ b\right\} }
\end{array}\right]
\]

\end_inset

so that the top row consists of the latest sequence values.
 When multiplied by the bits, this just generates the next iterate in the
 sequence.
 The upper-diagonal 1's just serve to shift columns over by one, with each
 iteration: that is why it's a shift!
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The product 
\begin_inset Formula $B^{m}J$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "Toeplitz matrix"
target "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Toeplitz_matrix"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The characteristic polynomial of this matrix is, of course, the polynomial
 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{n}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\det\left[B-xI\right]=\left(-1\right)^{k}p_{n}\left(x\right)
\]

\end_inset

Thus, we can trivially conclude that the eigenvalues of 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 are given by the roots of 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{n}\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

.
 This matrix is in lower-Hessenberg form; this makes it obvious that it's
 a shift; a finite shift, in this case.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Equivalent labels for orbits
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are many equivalent ways of labeling the various expressions and propertie
s under consideration.
 These are recapped here.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Orbits
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For every given 
\begin_inset Formula $1<\beta<2$
\end_inset

 there is a unique orbit of midpoints 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ m_{p}\right\} $
\end_inset

 given by 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{p}=T_{\beta}\left(m_{p-1}\right)=T_{\beta}^{p}\left(m_{0}\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{0}=\beta/2$
\end_inset

.
 The orbits are in one-to-one correspondence with 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

.
 The midpoints are the same as the Parry sequence; namely 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{\beta}^{p}\left(\beta/2\right)=\left(\beta/2\right)t_{\beta}^{p}\left(1\right)$
\end_inset

, recalling here the notation of eqn 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:beta transform"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:invariant measure"

\end_inset

.
 Some orbits are of finite length; the rest are either eventually periodic,
 or are ergodic.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Orbit encoding
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The midpoint generates a unique sequence of bits 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ b\right\} =\left\{ b_{0},b_{1,},\cdots,b_{k},\cdots\right\} $
\end_inset

 given by the left-right moves of the mid-point, as it is iterated.
 That is, 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{k}=\Theta\left(m_{k}-1/2\right)$
\end_inset

 so that 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{k}$
\end_inset

 is one if the midpoint is greater than half, else 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{k}$
\end_inset

 is zero.
 Each bit-sequence is in one-to-one correspondence with 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

.
 Finite orbits have finite-length sequences.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Monotonicity
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The compressor function 
\begin_inset Formula $w\left(\beta\right)=\sum_{k}b_{k}2^{-k}$
\end_inset

 is a monotonically increasing function of 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

, so that values of 
\begin_inset Formula $w\left(\beta\right)$
\end_inset

 are in one-to-one correspondence with 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Polynomial numbering
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If the orbit is finite, then there exists a polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{n}\left(z\right)=z^{k+1}-b_{0}z^{k}-b_{1}z^{k-1}-\cdots-b_{k-1}z-1$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $k=1+\left\lfloor \log_{2}\left(2n+1\right)\right\rfloor $
\end_inset

 being the length of the orbit.
 The positive real root 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{n}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{n}\left(r_{n}\right)=0$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta=r_{n}$
\end_inset

.
 That is, the iteratioin of 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{n}$
\end_inset

 will generate the finite-length bit-sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ b\right\} =\left\{ b_{0},b_{1,},\cdots,b_{k}\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 The integer 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is in one-to-one correspondence with the bit sequence, and with the value
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

.
 The integer is explicitly given by 
\begin_inset Formula $2n+1=\sum_{j=0}^{k}2^{j}b_{j}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If the orbit is not finite, there is a function 
\begin_inset Formula $q^{\left\{ b\right\} }\left(\zeta\right)=1-\sum_{j=0}^{\infty}b_{j}\zeta^{j+1}$
\end_inset

 holomorphic on the unit disk, having one unique positive real zero 
\begin_inset Formula $q^{\left\{ b\right\} }\left(r_{\left\{ b\right\} }\right)=0$
\end_inset

 where this 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{\left\{ b\right\} }=1/\beta$
\end_inset

 is the same 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 that generated the bit-sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ b\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 Iterating 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{\left\{ b\right\} }$
\end_inset

 generates 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ b\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ b\right\} $
\end_inset

 is finite, then 
\begin_inset Formula $q^{\left\{ b\right\} }\left(\zeta\right)=\zeta^{k+1}p_{n}\left(1/\zeta\right)$
\end_inset

, so these functions agree on finite-length sequences.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Brackets
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If the orbit is finite, then there exists a unique bracketing relationship
 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell\Mapsto n\Mapsfrom\rho$
\end_inset

 for which 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is the polynomial index.
 The left and right bounds 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell,\rho$
\end_inset

 are strictly smaller indexes: 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell<n$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho<n$
\end_inset

, and even more strongly, 
\begin_inset Formula $2\ell\le n$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $2\rho\le n$
\end_inset

 that have the property of bounding the positive real roots of the corresponding
 polynomials: 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{\ell}<r_{n}<r_{\rho}$
\end_inset

, with 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{\ell}\left(r_{\ell}\right)=p_{n}\left(r_{n}\right)=p_{\rho}\left(r_{\rho}\right)=0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Binary tree
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Each bracket is in one-to-one correspondence with a node in the full, unbounded
 binary tree.
 Sub-brackets define left and right subintervals that are disjoint, and
 whose union makes up the whole interval.
 Every node in the full binary tree can be labelled with a unique sequence
 of left-right moves to get to that node.
 This places the brackets (and thus, the polynomials and the roots and the
 mid-point orbits) in unique, one-to-one correspondences with finite-length
 strings of L,R moves.
 Such strings are, in turn, in one-to-one correspondence with the dyadic
 rationals.
 The L,R strings are in one-to-one correspondence with the orbits 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ b\right\} $
\end_inset

 but they are 
\emph on
not
\emph default
 numerically the same! This are distinct sequences! In particular, all possible
 L,R moves are allowed.
 Only a limited number of orbits 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ b\right\} $
\end_inset

 are possible, as limited by necklace-counting considerations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Baire sequences
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If the orbit is finite, then there exists a unique integer sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[m_{1},m_{2},\cdots,m_{k}\right]$
\end_inset

 such that the index is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta\left[m_{1},m_{2},\cdots,m_{k}\right]$
\end_inset

.
 This is a bijection between all valid indexes and all possible finite-length
 sequences.
 Due to the bounding property of the brackets, limits of 
\begin_inset Formula $k\to\infty$
\end_inset

 can be taken, and these limits are unique.
 Thus, all 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 values, including those with non-finite orbits, can be placed in a one-to-one
 bijection with infinite-length sequences 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[m_{1},m_{2},\cdots\right]\in\mathbb{N}^{\omega}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Beta-Fibonacci sequences
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If the orbit is finite, then there exists a sequence of integers 
\begin_inset Formula $F^{\{b\}}$
\end_inset

, the beta-Fibonacci sequence, that is in one-to-one correspondence with
 the finite bit sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ b\right\} =b_{0},b_{1},\cdots,b_{k}$
\end_inset

, and with the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

.
 There are also sequences for each infinite-length orbit 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ b\right\} $
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Shift matrix
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If the orbit is finite, then the finite bit sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ b\right\} =b_{0},b_{1},\cdots,b_{k}$
\end_inset

 defines a lower-Hessenberg 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

golden shift
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

, as shown in eqn 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:golden matrix"

\end_inset

.
 The limit of 
\begin_inset Formula $k\to\infty$
\end_inset

 can be taken in a relatively straight-forward manner, given below.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Summary
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To summarize: any one of these: the integer 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

, the polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{n}\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

, the bracket location in the binary tree, a dyadic rational, a point in
 Baire space, the integer sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{m}^{\left\{ b\right\} }$
\end_inset

, the orbit of midpoints 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{p}=T^{p}\left(\beta/2\right)$
\end_inset

, the orbit encoding 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ b\right\} $
\end_inset

, the shift matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

, the value of the compressor function 
\begin_inset Formula $w\left(\beta\right)$
\end_inset

 and, of course, 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 itself can each be used as a stand-in for the others, as they are all in
 one-to-one correspondence.
 Specifying one determines the others; all uniquely map to one-another.
 The formulas that provide maps between each of these can all be given in
 closed form, except for the handful of resursively-defined formulas.
 The recursive formulas are all invertable; thus they are computerable (decidabl
e).
 They are all equivalent labels.
 Fashionably abusing notation, 
\begin_inset Formula $n\equiv p_{n}\left(x\right)\equiv r_{n}\equiv\left\{ b\right\} \equiv F_{m}^{\left\{ b\right\} }\equiv m_{p}\equiv w\left(\beta\right)\equiv\beta\equiv B$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An explicit expression relating the orbit encoding and the orbit can be
 read off directly from eqn 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:iterated shift"

\end_inset

.
 Plugging in, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
m_{p}=T_{\beta}^{p+1}\left(\frac{\beta}{2}\right)=\frac{\beta}{2}\left[\beta^{p+1}-\sum_{j=0}^{p}b_{j}\beta^{p-j}\right]\label{eq:midpoint poly}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

for 
\begin_inset Formula $p<k$
\end_inset

 the length of the bit sequence, and 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{k}=T_{\beta}^{k+1}\left(\beta/2\right)=\beta p_{n}\left(\beta\right)/2=0$
\end_inset

 terminating, since 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 is the positive root of 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{n}\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Four of the correspondences given above ask for finite orbits.
 Three of these can be extended to non-finite orbits in an unambiguous and
 uncontroversial way.
 The extensions are covered in the next two sections.
 The fourth is the numbering 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 of the finite orbits.
 These are countable; there is no way to extend the counting number 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 to the non-finite orbits.
 Indeed, there are too many: the non-finite orbits are uncountable.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Eventually-periodic orbits
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The previous section characterized the set of 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 values which have midpoint orbits of finite length.
 Another interesting class is the set of eventually-periodic orbits: orbits
 of infinite length, settling down to a stable, periodic cycle after an
 initial bout of chaotic motion.
 These 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 values occur as the roots of a slightly different set of self-describing
 polynomials, as a sum of two parts: one for the initial chaotic motion,
 and a second polynomial for the cyclic motion.
 These can be (monotonically) paired with the rational numbers, with infinite
 paths through the binary tree, and with locations on the comb function.
 They naturally extend the bracket mapping from the dyadic rationals to
 all rational numbers.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Bitsequence polynomials
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider the set of all eventually-periodic bit-sequences.
 These consist of a leading chaotic prefix of length 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 followed by a periodic orbit of length 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

.
 Such sequences can be placed in one-to-one correspondence with the rationals,
 in the conventional fashion.
 Select such a sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ b_{k}\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 The cyclic condition has that 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{k}=b_{k+N}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $k\ge L$
\end_inset

.
 Split this into two parts: a finite length-
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 digit sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{k}=b_{k}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $k<L$
\end_inset

 and a finite length-
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 cyclic bit sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{k}=b_{k+L}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $k<N$
\end_inset

.
 Associated to this is rational number 
\begin_inset Formula $x=\sum_{k=0}^{\infty}b_{k}2^{-k-1}$
\end_inset

.
 To get it's value, write
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
S\left(\beta\right)= & \sum_{k=0}^{\infty}b_{k}\beta^{-k}\\
= & \sum_{k=0}^{L-1}b_{k}\beta^{-k}+\sum_{k=L}^{L+N-1}b_{k}\beta^{-k}+\sum_{k=L+N}^{L+2N-1}b_{k}\beta^{-k}+\cdots\\
= & \sum_{k=0}^{L-1}b_{k}\beta^{-k}+\frac{\beta^{N}}{\beta^{N}-1}\sum_{k=L}^{L+N-1}b_{k}\beta^{-k}\\
= & \frac{1}{\beta^{L-1}}\sum_{k=0}^{L-1}d_{k}\beta^{L-k-1}+\frac{1}{\beta^{L-1}\left(\beta^{N}-1\right)}\sum_{k=0}^{N-1}c_{k}\beta^{N-k-1}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Plugging in 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta=2$
\end_inset

 gives ratios of whole numbers: a rational that corresponds to this bit-sequence.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Any given 
\begin_inset Formula $1\le\beta\le2$
\end_inset

 generates a mid-point orbit bit-sequence.
 Sadly, we've introduced too many different but equivalent notations for
 this.
 Starting with the mid-point 
\begin_inset Formula $x=m_{0}=\beta/2$
\end_inset

, the characteristic bit-sequence is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
b_{n}=\Theta\left(m_{n}-\frac{1}{2}\right)=\Theta\left(T_{\beta}^{n}\left(\frac{\beta}{2}\right)-\frac{1}{2}\right)=d_{n}\left(\frac{1}{2}\right)=k_{n}\left(\frac{\beta}{2}\right)=\varepsilon_{n}\left(\frac{1}{\beta}\right)
\]

\end_inset

Such orbits have the self-describing property, that 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta=S\left(\beta\right)$
\end_inset

.
 This follows from eqn 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:shift series"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, as well as other identities.
 For the eventually-periodic orbits, 
\begin_inset Formula $S\left(\beta\right)$
\end_inset

 is a ratio of polynomials.
 It can clearly be placed in one-to-one correspondence with the rationals.
 It is not hard to show that it has one unique real root 
\begin_inset Formula $1<\beta\le2$
\end_inset

, and so these are in one-to-one correspondence as well.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This can be related to earlier notation.
 Writing 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta-S\left(\beta\right)=0$
\end_inset

 and then multiplying through by the denominator, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(\beta^{N}-1\right)\left(\beta^{L}-\sum_{k=0}^{L-1}d_{k}\beta^{L-1-k}\right)-\sum_{k=0}^{N-1}c_{k}\beta^{N-1-k}=0
\]

\end_inset

This touches the earlier notation for the polynomials describing finite
 orbits:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p^{\left\{ d_{0}\cdots d_{\nu-1}\right\} }\left(\beta\right)=\beta^{\nu}-\sum_{k=0}^{\nu-1}d_{k}\beta^{\nu-1-k}
\]

\end_inset

and so the eventually-periodic orbits are the roots of
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(\beta^{N}-1\right)p^{\left\{ d_{0}\cdots d_{L-1}\right\} }\left(\beta\right)+p^{\left\{ c_{0}\cdots c_{N-1}\right\} }\left(\beta\right)-\beta^{N}=0
\]

\end_inset

Finite-length orbits have 
\begin_inset Formula $N=1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{0}=0$
\end_inset

, so that the cyclic term vanishes, and the earlier form is recovered, after
 ignoring an extra factor of 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta-1$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finite-length orbits can be converted to infinite-length periodic orbits
 simply by setting the last bit to zero, and then repeating the bit sequence
 cyclically.
 Recall, finite orbits always have the last bit equal to one, so this operation
 is always unambiguous.
 Restating this explicitly: if 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{0}b_{1}\cdots b_{\nu-1}$
\end_inset

 is a finite-length orbit, then set 
\begin_inset Formula $L=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $N=\nu$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{k}=b_{k}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $k<\nu-1$
\end_inset

 and finally 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{\nu-1}=0$
\end_inset

.
 Plugging through just yields the usual polynomial for finite orbits.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Collecting terms of the same order, write
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
0=\beta^{N+L}-\sum_{k=0}^{N+L-1}a_{k}\beta^{N+L-1-k}
\]

\end_inset

The coefficients are then
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a_{k}=d_{k}+c_{k-L}+\delta_{k-N-1}^{0}-d_{k-N}
\]

\end_inset

with 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

 the Kronecker delta.
 The only coefficients that can appear are in the set 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{k}\in\left\{ -1,0,1,2\right\} $
\end_inset

, and at most one coefficient can be 2; it is specifically 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{N-1}$
\end_inset

, which can only ever be 1 or 2.
 This can be best understood visually, lining up columns.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $L>N$
\end_inset

, get 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{k}$
\end_inset

 by summing the columns:
\begin_inset VSpace defskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

