\begin_layout Subsection
Infinite-nacci integer sequences 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The beta-Fibonacci integer sequence can be extended to arbitrary (
\emph on
viz.

\emph default
 infinite) length bit sequences, as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
F_{m}^{\{b\}}=\sum_{j=1}^{m}b_{j-1}F_{m-j}^{\{b\}}
\]

\end_inset

starting with 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{0}^{\left\{ b\right\} }=1$
\end_inset

.
 The sum is always finite, but one cannot perform it without first knowing
 at least the first 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 bits of the (now infinite) bit-sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ b\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 The integer sequence still has the desirable property it had before: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\beta=\lim_{m\to\infty}\frac{F_{m}^{\{b\}}}{F_{m-1}^{\{b\}}}
\]

\end_inset

Here, the 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 value is the one associated to 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ b\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 So, as before, the real number 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 and the bit sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ b\right\} $
\end_inset

 label exactly the same orbit.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Remarkably, one can be sloppy in how one deals with finite orbits with this
 extension.
 One has two choices that are equivalent: One choice is to truncate, so
 that the bit-sequence ends with all-zeros, effectively rendering it of
 finite length.
 The alternative is to allow it to continue periodically, forever.
 Either form results in the same 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

-Fibonacci sequence! 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As an example, consider 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta=1.6$
\end_inset

, which is close to the golden ratio, but not quite.
 It has an infinite non-periodic (nonrecurring) bit-sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ b\right\} =101010010100101000000100\cdots$
\end_inset

.
 The generated integer sequence is 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{m}^{\{b\}}=1,1,1,2,3,5,8,12,20,32,51,82,130,209,335,535,\cdots$
\end_inset

 which undershoots the Fibonacci sequence (12 appears, where we expected
 13, and 20 instead of 21, and so on).
 The ratio of the last two is 
\begin_inset Formula $535/335=1.597\cdots$
\end_inset

 and the previous is 
\begin_inset Formula $335/209=1.603\cdots$
\end_inset

 and the ratio of successive elements eventually converges to 1.6.
 By comparison, the Fibonacci sequence is generated by the bit-string 1010101010...
 of alternating ones and zeros.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

-Fibonacci representation of the orbits has the remarkable property that
 one does not need some 
\emph on
a priori
\emph default
 mechanism to know if some orbit is finite or not.
 This dual representation of finite orbits is reminiscent of a property
 commonly seen in Cantor space 
\begin_inset Formula $2^{\omega}$
\end_inset

 representations of the real number line, where the dyadic rationals (which
 are countable, of course) map to two distinct bit-sequences (one ending
 in all-ones, the other ending in all-zeros).
 A more general setting for this is given in symbolic dynamics, where the
 totally disconnected Bernoulli scheme 
\begin_inset Formula $N^{\omega}$
\end_inset

 can be used to represent elements of certain countable sets two different
 ways.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $N=10$
\end_inset

, one famously has that 1.000...=0.999...
 as an example.
 So likewise here, one can toggle between finite and infinite-periodic strings.
 So, given a finite string 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ b\right\} =b_{0},b_{1},\cdots,b_{k-1},b_{k}$
\end_inset

 which has, by definition, 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{k}=1$
\end_inset

, create a new finite string that is twice as long: 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ b^{\prime}\right\} =b_{0},b_{1},\cdots,b_{k-1},0,b_{0},b_{1},\cdots,b_{k}$
\end_inset

 which necessarily has exactly the same beta-Fiboanacci sequence.
 That is, 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{m}^{\{b^{\prime}\}}=F_{m}^{\{b\}}$
\end_inset

.
 Once can repeat this process 
\emph on
ad infinitum
\emph default
, obtaining an infinite periodic string.
 The difference between these two is simply the difference between a less-than
 sign, and a less-than-or-equal sign used in the generation of the orbit,
 as noted at the very beginning of this chapter.
 We have proven: finite orbits are exactly the same as infinite periodic
 orbits, at least when represented by real numbers and by integer sequences.
 Conversely, the difference between using 
\begin_inset Formula $<$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\le$
\end_inset

 during iteration is immaterial for describing convergents.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Infinite 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

-Polynomials
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An infinite polynomial is, of course, an analytic function.
 The goal here is to extend the finite framework.
 The definition of the polynomials above requires a finite bit sequence.
 This can be extended to an asymptotic series, by writing first
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p_{n}\left(z\right)=z^{k+1}\left(1-b_{0}z^{-1}-b_{1}z^{-2}-\cdots-b_{k}z^{-k-1}\right)
\]

\end_inset

Set 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta=1/z$
\end_inset

 to get
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\zeta^{k+1}p_{n}\left(\frac{1}{\zeta}\right)=1-b_{0}\zeta-b_{1}\zeta^{2}-\cdots-b_{k}\zeta^{k+1}
\]

\end_inset

which extends to the holomorphic function
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
q^{\left\{ b\right\} }\left(\zeta\right)=1-\sum_{j=0}^{\infty}b_{j}\zeta^{j+1}
\]

\end_inset

This is manifestly holomorphic on the unit disk, as each coefficient is
 either zero or one.
 It has a positive real zero, of course: 
\begin_inset Formula $q^{\left\{ b\right\} }\left(1/\beta\right)=0$
\end_inset

.
 Comparing to eqn 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:holomorphic-disk"

\end_inset

, we see that this is exactly the same function, or rather, it's negative.
 Indeed, following the definition, 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{n}=d_{n}\left(1/2\right)$
\end_inset

 and so 
\begin_inset Formula $E\left(\beta;\zeta\right)=-q^{\left\{ b\right\} }\left(\zeta\right)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This at last provides a foot in the door for correctly describing the eigenvalue
s of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

-transfer operator: they are in one-to-one correspondence with the zeros
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $q^{\left\{ b\right\} }\left(\zeta\right)$
\end_inset

.
 As before, though, this only exposes a discrete spectrum in the region
 
\begin_inset Formula $1/\beta<\left|\lambda\right|\le1$
\end_inset

; if there is any spectrum outside this region, the methods here cannot
 access it.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

-Hessenberg operator
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Extending the golden shift matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 of eqn 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:golden matrix"

\end_inset

 to an infinite-dimensional operator is a bit trickier.
 Of course, one could just declare the matrix elements of the operator to
 be this-and-such, but these matrix elements are with respect to what basis?
 Is the operator even bounded? The answer to the second question is obviously
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

no
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The characteristic equation of 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\det\left(B-\lambda I\right)=p_{n}\left(\lambda\right)=0$
\end_inset

; the Frobenius-Perron eigenvalue 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta>1$
\end_inset

 is too large, although the 
\begin_inset Formula $k-1=\left\lfloor \log_{2}n\right\rfloor $
\end_inset

 other roots are conveniently arranged near the unit circle, more-or-less
 equidistant from one another.
 The solution is to rescale 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $1/\beta$
\end_inset

.
 The Frobenius-Perron eigenvalue is now one, and the remaining eigenvalues
 distributed near or on a circle of radius 
\begin_inset Formula $1/\beta$
\end_inset

.
 We may as well take the transpose as well, so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{H}_{\beta}=B^{T}/\beta$
\end_inset

 is in upper-Hessenberg form.
 Rescaled in this way, it now seems safe to declare, by fiat, that the operator
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{H}_{\beta}$
\end_inset

 is the correct extension of the matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 to infinite dimensions.
 Just to be explicit: given the bit-sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ b\right\} $
\end_inset

, the operator
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{H}_{\beta}$
\end_inset

 has the matrix elements
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\left\langle 0\left|\mathcal{H}_{\beta}\right|j\right\rangle  & =\frac{b_{j}}{\beta}\\
\left\langle j+1\left|\mathcal{H}_{\beta}\right|j\right\rangle  & =\frac{1}{\beta}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

with all other entries being zero.
 This is clearly in upper-Hessenberg form, with the subdiagonal providing
 the shift.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Comparing to the upper-Hessenberg form of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{\beta}$
\end_inset

 of eqn 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:hessen-matrix-elts"

\end_inset

, and the numerical results on it's eigenvalues, it seems clear that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{H}_{\beta}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{\beta}$
\end_inset

 must surely be similar.
 That is, there must be an operator 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 such that 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{L}_{\beta}=S^{-1}\mathcal{H}_{\beta}S
\]

\end_inset

The invariant measure 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{\beta}\rho=\rho$
\end_inset

 is mapped to 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma=S\rho$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{H}_{\beta}\sigma=\sigma$
\end_inset

 is the FP-eigenvector.
 It is easy to write down 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 explicitly: 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma=\left(1,\beta^{-1},\beta^{-2},\cdots\right)$
\end_inset

, that is, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{j}=\beta^{-j}$
\end_inset

.
 This is obviously so: the subdiagonal entries of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}_{\beta}$
\end_inset

 act as a shift on 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 and the top row is just
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
1=\sum_{j=0}^{\infty}\left\langle 0\left|\mathcal{H}_{\beta}\right|j\right\rangle \sigma_{j}=\sum_{j=0}^{\infty}b_{j}\beta^{-j-1}=1-q^{\left\{ b\right\} }\left(\frac{1}{\beta}\right)=1
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Although 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{H}_{\beta}$
\end_inset

 is no more solvable than 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{\beta}$
\end_inset

 in the wavelet basis is, it is certainly much, much easier to work with.
 It also reaffirms the Ansatz 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:coherent-first-order"

\end_inset

 for eigenfunctions.
 To be explicit: if 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 is a vector satisfying 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{H}_{\beta}v=\lambda v$
\end_inset

, with vector elements 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{j}$
\end_inset

, then the function
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
v\left(x\right)=\sum_{j=0}^{\infty}d_{j}\left(x\right)v_{j}
\]

\end_inset

 is an eigenfunction of the transfer operator: that is, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\mathcal{L}_{\beta}v\right]\left(x\right)=\lambda v\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

, or, explicitly:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{1}{\beta}\left[v\left(\frac{x}{\beta}\right)+v\left(\frac{x}{\beta}+\frac{1}{2}\right)\right]\Theta\left(\frac{\beta}{2}-x\right)=\lambda v\left(x\right)\label{eq:fundamental-shift}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

which is just eqn 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:xfer oper"

\end_inset

.
 So, for 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=1$
\end_inset

, this is just 
\begin_inset Formula $v=\sigma$
\end_inset

 which is just eqn 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:coherent-first-order"

\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $z=1$
\end_inset

, the invariant measure, as always.
 But it also says more: the 
\emph on
only
\emph default
 solutions to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{H}_{\beta}v=\lambda v$
\end_inset

 are necessarily of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $v=\left(1,\left(\lambda\beta\right)^{-1},\left(\lambda\beta\right)^{-2},\cdots\right)$
\end_inset

, because the subdiagonal forces this shift.
 To satisfy the the top row of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{H}_{\beta}$
\end_inset

, one must have that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\lambda=\sum_{j=0}^{\infty}\left\langle 0\left|\mathcal{H}_{\beta}\right|j\right\rangle v_{j}=\frac{1}{\beta}\sum_{j=0}^{\infty}\frac{b_{j}}{\left(\lambda\beta\right)^{j}}=\lambda\left(1-q^{\left\{ b\right\} }\left(\frac{1}{\lambda\beta}\right)\right)=\lambda
\]

\end_inset

and so the eigenvalue 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 is exactly the eigenvalue that solves the 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

-series 
\begin_inset Formula $q^{\left\{ b\right\} }\left(1/\lambda\beta\right)=0$
\end_inset

.
 This effectively concludes a proof: the solutions to this series are the
 only eigenvalues of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

-transfer operator; there are no others.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To recap: finite orbits have an associated shift matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

; this extends naturally to a shift operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{H}_{\beta}$
\end_inset

 for non-finite orbits.
 The shift operator has a sufficiently simple form that it's eigenvectors
 can be explicitly written down in closed form; they are necessarily coherent
 states
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The term 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

coherent states
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 comes from quantum optics: a state that can be written as an analytic series
 over states/vectors expressed in a different basis.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 The top row of the shift operator defines a holomorphic function 
\begin_inset Formula $q^{\left\{ b\right\} }$
\end_inset

 whose zeros correspond to eigenstates of the shift operator.
 The holomorphic function is determined by the binary digit sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ b\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 The binary digit sequence is obtained from the iterated midpoint, as 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{j}=d_{j}\left(1/2\right)$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{j}\left(x\right)=1$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $x<T^{n}\left(\beta/2\right)$
\end_inset

.
 This is enough to prove eqn 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:fundamental-shift"

\end_inset

 holds for the special value 
\begin_inset Formula $x=0$
\end_inset

 (for 
\emph on
any
\emph default
 eigenvalue 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

).
 It was previously proven that the vanishing of 
\begin_inset Formula $q^{\left\{ b\right\} }$
\end_inset

 is independent of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, 
\emph on
i.e.

\emph default
 that eqn 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:fundamental-shift"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 holds for any 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Eigenfunctions from finite orbits
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To recap: eigenstates of the transfer operator correspond with the zeros
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $q^{\left\{ b\right\} }\left(\zeta\right)$
\end_inset

, or, more precisely, the zeros for which 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\zeta\right|\le1$
\end_inset

.
 The reason for this limitation is that the eigenstates are explicitly given
 by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
v\left(x\right)=\sum_{m=0}^{\infty}d_{m}\left(x\right)\zeta^{m}
\]

\end_inset

for 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta=1/\beta\lambda$
\end_inset

; this is absolutely convergent only for 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\zeta\right|<1$
\end_inset

.
 One might hope to analytically continue this to the entire complex plane,
 but the continuation depends on the digit sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{m}\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

.
 One might expect that an analytic continuation is impossible, as the 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{m}\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 are ergodic, and thus throws up some kind of essential singularity at 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\zeta\right|=1$
\end_inset

 that cannot be continued past.
 We are lacking in tools and language to discuss this situation.
 Perhaps some insight can be gleaned by examining the periodic orbits...
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Case n=1
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider first 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta=\varphi=1.6180\cdots$
\end_inset

 the golden ratio.
 The corresponding finite beta-polynomial is 
\begin_inset Formula $q^{\left\{ 11\right\} }\left(\zeta\right)=1-\zeta-\zeta^{2}$
\end_inset

; the infinite series is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
q^{\left\{ 1010101\cdots\right\} }\left(\zeta\right)=1-\zeta-\zeta^{3}-\zeta^{5}-\cdots=\left(1-\zeta-\zeta^{2}\right)/\left(1-\zeta^{2}\right)
\]

\end_inset

which has a positive real zero at 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta=1/\varphi$
\end_inset

 and poles at 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta=\pm1$
\end_inset

.
 The zero corresponds to the FP eigenvalue of one.
 The invariant measure is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
v\left(x\right)=\sum_{m=0}^{\infty}\frac{d_{m}\left(x\right)}{\varphi^{m}}=\begin{cases}
\varphi & \mbox{for }0\le x<\frac{1}{2}\\
1 & \mbox{for }\frac{1}{2}\le x<\varphi\\
0 & \mbox{for }\varphi\le x
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset

There is a negative real zero at 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta=-\varphi$
\end_inset

, but the eigenfunction summation is not convergent here.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Case n=2
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\begin_inset Formula $n=2$
\end_inset

 case has the finite bitstring 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ b\right\} =101$
\end_inset

 and the periodic bitstring 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ b\right\} =1001001\cdots$
\end_inset

.
 The corresponding finite beta-polynomial is 
\begin_inset Formula $q^{\left\{ 101\right\} }\left(\zeta\right)=1-\zeta-\zeta^{3}$
\end_inset

; the infinite series is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
q^{\left\{ 1001\cdots\right\} }\left(\zeta\right)=1-\zeta-\zeta^{4}-\zeta^{7}-\cdots=\left(1-\zeta-\zeta^{3}\right)/\left(1-\zeta^{3}\right)
\]

\end_inset

which has a positive real zero at 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta=1/\beta=0.6823\cdots$
\end_inset

 and three poles on the unit circle.
 The FP eigenvalue provides 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta=1.4655\cdots$
\end_inset

.
 The invariant measure is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
v\left(x\right)=\sum_{m=0}^{\infty}\frac{d_{m}\left(x\right)}{\beta^{m}}=\begin{cases}
\frac{\beta}{\beta-1} & \mbox{for }0\le x<T\left(\frac{\beta}{2}\right)\\
\frac{1}{\beta-1} & \mbox{for }T\left(\frac{\beta}{2}\right)\le x<\frac{1}{2}\\
\frac{1/\beta}{\beta-1} & \mbox{for }\frac{1}{2}\le x<\beta\\
0 & \mbox{for }\beta\le x
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset

There are many equivalent ways to write the invariant measure; the above
 just selected some representatives from the coset of equivalent expressions.
 For example, the third entry could be written as 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta=1/\beta\left(\beta-1\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Case n=3
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\begin_inset Formula $n=3$
\end_inset

 case has the finite bitstring 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ b\right\} =111$
\end_inset

 and the periodic bitstring 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ b\right\} =1101101\cdots$
\end_inset

.
 The corresponding finite beta-polynomial is 
\begin_inset Formula $q^{\left\{ 111\right\} }\left(\zeta\right)=1-\zeta-\zeta^{2}-\zeta^{3}$
\end_inset

; the infinite series is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
q^{\left\{ 110110\cdots\right\} }\left(\zeta\right)=1-\zeta-\zeta^{2}-\zeta^{4}-\cdots=\left(1-\zeta-\zeta^{2}-\zeta^{3}\right)/\left(1-\zeta^{3}\right)
\]

\end_inset

which has a positive real zero at 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta=1/\beta=0.5436\cdots$
\end_inset

 and three poles on the unit circle.
 The FP eigenvalue gives 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta=1.8392\cdots$
\end_inset

.
 The invariant measure is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
v\left(x\right)=\begin{cases}
\frac{\beta}{\beta-1} & \mbox{for }0\le x<\frac{1}{2}\\
\beta & \mbox{for }\frac{1}{2}\le x<T\left(\frac{\beta}{2}\right)\\
\frac{1}{\beta-1} & \mbox{for }T\left(\frac{\beta}{2}\right)\le x<\beta\\
0 & \mbox{for }\beta\le x
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Case n=4,6,7
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The pattern gets repetitive.
 There is no case 
\begin_inset Formula $n=5$
\end_inset

, as this is not one of the allowed orbits.
 The bitstrings are those previously listed in tables; they are 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ b\right\} =1001$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ b\right\} =1101$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ b\right\} =1111$
\end_inset

.
 The infinite series is 
\begin_inset Formula $q^{\left\{ b\cdots\right\} }\left(\zeta\right)=q^{\left\{ b\right\} }\left(\zeta\right)/\left(1-\zeta^{4}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 The zeros are as previously listed.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $n=4$
\end_inset

 plateaus are at 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{\beta-1}\left[\begin{array}{cccc}
\beta, & 1, & \frac{1}{\beta}, & \frac{1}{\beta^{2}}\end{array}\right]$
\end_inset

.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $n=6$
\end_inset

 plateaus are at 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\begin{array}{cccc}
\frac{\beta}{\beta-1}, & \frac{\beta^{2}}{\left(\beta^{2}-1\right)\left(\beta-1\right)}, & \beta, & \frac{\beta}{\left(\beta^{2}-1\right)\left(\beta-1\right)}\end{array}\right]$
\end_inset

.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $n=7$
\end_inset

 plateaus are at 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\begin{array}{cccc}
\frac{\beta}{\beta-1}, & \beta, & \frac{\beta+1}{\beta\left(\beta-1\right)}, & \frac{1}{\beta-1}\end{array}\right]$
\end_inset

.
 Again, the values at the plateaus can be written in many different ways,
 given the finite polynomial.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Case n=16
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\begin_inset Formula $n=16$
\end_inset

 polynomial is the first one to have complex zeros inside the unit disk.
 The finite bitstring is 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ b\right\} =100001$
\end_inset

 and so the polynomial is 
\begin_inset Formula $q^{\left\{ 100001\right\} }\left(\zeta\right)=1-\zeta-\zeta^{6}$
\end_inset

.
 The positive real root is 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta=0.7780895986786\cdots$
\end_inset

 and so 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta=1/\zeta=1.28519903324535\cdots$
\end_inset

.
 The complex zeros are located at 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta=0.965709509\cdots\exp\pm i\pi0.2740452363\cdots$
\end_inset

 which corresponds to the eigenvalues 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=0.525107\cdots\pm i0.611100\cdots=0.805718\cdots\exp\pm i\pi0.274045\cdots$
\end_inset

.
 The corresponding eigenfunction is shown immediately below.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename period-n16.eps
	width 60col%

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The order of 
\begin_inset Formula $q^{\left\{ b\right\} }$
\end_inset

 is six, and this has six almost-plateaus; they are not quite flat, although
 they are close to it, presumably because 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta$
\end_inset

 is close to one.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
The general case
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Generalizing from the above, one finds the following:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
For a period-
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 orbit, the infinite series is 
\begin_inset Formula $q^{\left\{ b\cdots\right\} }\left(\zeta\right)=q^{\left\{ b\right\} }\left(\zeta\right)/\left(1-\zeta^{k}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The first label 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 for which 
\begin_inset Formula $q^{\left\{ b\right\} }\left(\zeta\right)$
\end_inset

 has a complex zero within the disk is 
\begin_inset Formula $n=16$
\end_inset

.
 As a general rule, it seems that complex zeros inside the disk only appear
 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta<\varphi$
\end_inset

 (I believe; have not carefully checked.
 This seems reasonable, as later chapters show that the region of 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta<\varphi$
\end_inset

 behaves very differently from larger values.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The invariant measure has 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 plateaus.
 The plateau boundaries are given by 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{m}\left(\frac{1}{2}\right)$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $m=\left\{ 0,\cdots,k-1\right\} $
\end_inset

 (so that 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{0}\left(\frac{1}{2}\right)=\frac{1}{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{1}\left(\frac{1}{2}\right)=\frac{\beta}{2}$
\end_inset

, and so on).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The leftmost plateau (of the invariant measure) is at 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta/\left(\beta-1\right)=\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}1/\beta^{n}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The other plateaus appear to be at simple rational functions of 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

, but a precise expression is elusive.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To solve the last issue, perhaps one can find tools in Galois theory.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}\left[\zeta\right]$
\end_inset

 be the ring of polynomials in 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta$
\end_inset

 and consider the quotient ring 
\begin_inset Formula $L=\mathbb{R}\left[\zeta\right]/q^{\left\{ b\right\} }\left(\zeta\right)$
\end_inset

.
 This 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 is a field extension of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 and so one expects a Galois group 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{Gal}\left(L/\mathbb{R}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 The plateaus of the invariant measure are presumably associated with the
 group elements.
 This seems like a promising direction to go in: perhaps this is just enough
 to explain the length of an orbit, the sequence of points in the orbit,
 the reason that some polynomials are forbidden (they don't generate prime
 ideals), the appearance of Moreau's necklace-counting function,
\emph on
 etc
\emph default
.
 This remains an unfinished exercise.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Islands of Stability as Arnold Tongues
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Islands-of-Stability"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The trouble-spots, the eventual fixed-points of the map, can be placed in
 one-to-one accordance with the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

islands of stability
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 seen in the iterated logistic map.
 They are, in essence, locations where periodic orbits 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

could be pasted
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, or where they 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

naturally would appear
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, if the map supported periodic attractors.
 That is, the beta shift only supports a single attractor, of period-one
 at 
\begin_inset Formula $x=0$
\end_inset

; there is no 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

room
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 for anything more.
 This is analogous, in a way, to the phase locked loop, at zero coupling
 constant.
 At finite coupling strength, these 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

trouble spots
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 expand out as Arnold tongues, to have a finite size, visible on the Feigenbaum
 diagram for the logistic map as regions where period-doubling is occurring.
